WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.458 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.458 --> 00:00:02.916 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:02.916 --> 00:00:05.832 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.832 --> 00:00:11.415 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.415 --> 00:00:13.040 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So
today is the last day

00:00:13.040 --> 00:00:16.000 align:middle line:84%
of our unit about
random walks on groups.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.140 align:middle line:84%
And the goal of the
day is to digest,

00:00:20.140 --> 00:00:26.440 align:middle line:84%
think about the Bourgain-Gamburd
theorem about mixing on SL2(Fp).

00:00:26.440 --> 00:00:28.820 align:middle line:84%
So we stated it at the
end of last time-- first,

00:00:28.820 --> 00:00:31.530 align:middle line:84%
I'll remember to remind
everybody what it says.

00:00:31.530 --> 00:00:57.200 align:middle line:90%


00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:01.870 align:middle line:84%
OK, so it's about
mixing on SL2(Fp).

00:01:01.870 --> 00:01:13.057 align:middle line:84%
So it says if mu is a
probability measure, SL2(Fp).

00:01:13.057 --> 00:01:14.890 align:middle line:84%
Actually, maybe it
doesn't matter that much.

00:01:14.890 --> 00:01:17.060 align:middle line:84%
But maybe we set it
in terms of subsets.

00:01:17.060 --> 00:01:23.924 align:middle line:90%


00:01:23.924 --> 00:01:27.470 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the question is,
when does the random walk

00:01:27.470 --> 00:01:29.260 align:middle line:90%
coming from A mix?

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:32.915 align:middle line:90%


00:01:32.915 --> 00:01:38.670 align:middle line:84%
So then the conclusion will be,
the singular value of this walk

00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:41.030 align:middle line:84%
is less than 1
minus C of epsilon,

00:01:41.030 --> 00:01:43.470 align:middle line:90%
meaning that it does mix.

00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:45.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:48.550 align:middle line:84%
And to see that this
happens, we need

00:01:48.550 --> 00:01:51.210 align:middle line:84%
to know that A doesn't
lie in any subgroup.

00:01:51.210 --> 00:01:53.830 align:middle line:84%
And so we have a hypothesis
that's related to that.

00:01:53.830 --> 00:02:05.460 align:middle line:84%
It says that for any Borel
subgroup B, A intersect gB--

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:06.850 align:middle line:90%
so any g in our group.

00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:11.420 align:middle line:90%


00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:14.900 align:middle line:84%
This guy is bounded
by K of epsilon p

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:19.700 align:middle line:84%
to the minus epsilon times A.
So only a small fraction of A

00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:24.220 align:middle line:84%
lies in any coset
of a Borel group.

00:02:24.220 --> 00:02:26.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:26.380 --> 00:02:28.940 align:middle line:84%
And we put in parentheses
that A is symmetric.

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:32.300 align:middle line:84%
We don't really need it, but it
also doesn't matter that much.

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:35.180 align:middle line:84%
And it will make things
a little cleaner.

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:35.740 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:37.740 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I have a question
about the difference

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:42.160 align:middle line:84%
between using a subset
versus a measure.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:44.620 align:middle line:84%
Is it possible to pass
between the two cases

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:47.583 align:middle line:84%
by weighting by
different subgroup sets?

00:02:47.583 --> 00:02:49.000 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH:
Yeah, that's right.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.375 align:middle line:84%
So the question was, what's
the difference between taking

00:02:51.375 --> 00:02:52.892 align:middle line:90%
a subset or taking a measure?

00:02:52.892 --> 00:02:54.600 align:middle line:84%
I think there's not
that much difference.

00:02:54.600 --> 00:02:56.540 align:middle line:84%
I think if you can use
this as a black box

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:58.068 align:middle line:84%
and prove things
about measures, I

00:02:58.068 --> 00:03:00.610 align:middle line:84%
think we also could just use
measures through the whole proof

00:03:00.610 --> 00:03:03.410 align:middle line:90%
and it would work fine.

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:04.650 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:04.650 --> 00:03:08.510 align:middle line:84%
So the proof of this theorem
breaks into two important pieces

00:03:08.510 --> 00:03:10.010 align:middle line:84%
which are both
interesting and which

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:12.510 align:middle line:84%
are both connected in different
ways to themes of our class.

00:03:12.510 --> 00:03:22.203 align:middle line:90%


00:03:22.203 --> 00:03:22.703 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:22.703 --> 00:03:26.154 align:middle line:90%


00:03:26.154 --> 00:03:30.690 align:middle line:84%
So the first part says that
if you just have pretty much

00:03:30.690 --> 00:03:33.590 align:middle line:84%
any set and you do
this random walk,

00:03:33.590 --> 00:03:36.090 align:middle line:84%
the only way it
can fail to mix is

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:38.850 align:middle line:84%
if it gets stuck
in something which

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:42.750 align:middle line:90%
is approximately a subgroup.

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:44.450 align:middle line:84%
So it can fail to
mix if it's literally

00:03:44.450 --> 00:03:45.450 align:middle line:90%
contained in a subgroup.

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:47.170 align:middle line:84%
And a little bit
more generally, it

00:03:47.170 --> 00:03:50.050 align:middle line:84%
can only fail to mix if
there's a set which is a lot

00:03:50.050 --> 00:03:54.530 align:middle line:84%
like a subgroup which contains a
lot of the mass of the measure.

00:03:54.530 --> 00:03:56.370 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to write this down.

00:03:56.370 --> 00:04:02.310 align:middle line:90%


00:04:02.310 --> 00:04:05.510 align:middle line:84%
So this is probably
true for any group.

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:08.013 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to write it
for SL2(Fp) for now.

00:04:08.013 --> 00:04:09.430 align:middle line:84%
And then as we
talk about it more,

00:04:09.430 --> 00:04:11.890 align:middle line:84%
let's keep our eyes open
of what we actually used.

00:04:11.890 --> 00:04:16.470 align:middle line:90%


00:04:16.470 --> 00:04:20.149 align:middle line:90%
This is symmetric.

00:04:20.149 --> 00:04:26.560 align:middle line:84%
And sigma 1 TA is
bigger than 1 minus--

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:30.370 align:middle line:90%


00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:30.870 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:35.540 align:middle line:90%
Here I'll put 1 minus epsilon.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:42.950 align:middle line:84%
And then there exists some kind
of approximate subgroup called

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:53.610 align:middle line:90%
H. Yeah, hold on.

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:55.860 align:middle line:90%
Let me adjust it a little bit.

00:04:55.860 --> 00:04:59.860 align:middle line:84%
Let me also say that
A is pretty big.

00:04:59.860 --> 00:05:03.020 align:middle line:90%
It is not too tiny.

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:11.540 align:middle line:84%
Then there exists some H so that
mu tensored to some power of H

00:05:11.540 --> 00:05:12.370 align:middle line:90%
is pretty big.

00:05:12.370 --> 00:05:18.220 align:middle line:90%


00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:22.990 align:middle line:84%
And this H is sort of like a
subgroup in the following sense.

00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:28.180 align:middle line:90%


00:05:28.180 --> 00:05:31.600 align:middle line:84%
So H, if you multiply it
by itself many times--

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:32.340 align:middle line:90%
for example, 5.

00:05:32.340 --> 00:05:34.060 align:middle line:90%
You could do more.

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:37.380 align:middle line:84%
This is less than p to
the O of delta times

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:40.280 align:middle line:90%
H. And H also is not too big.

00:05:40.280 --> 00:05:44.980 align:middle line:90%


00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:46.740 align:middle line:84%
OK, so if you had
another group, you

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:48.280 align:middle line:84%
would have to
adjust these things.

00:05:48.280 --> 00:05:49.877 align:middle line:90%
But I think that that's minor.

00:05:49.877 --> 00:05:51.710 align:middle line:84%
I think that's all you
would have to change.

00:05:51.710 --> 00:05:54.410 align:middle line:90%


00:05:54.410 --> 00:05:55.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:58.010 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a set which
is a decent sized fraction

00:05:58.010 --> 00:06:01.490 align:middle line:84%
of our group-- and let's
say it's symmetric--

00:06:01.490 --> 00:06:08.210 align:middle line:84%
then either that random walks
mixes or there is some subset

00:06:08.210 --> 00:06:10.490 align:middle line:90%
which is sort of like a group.

00:06:10.490 --> 00:06:15.030 align:middle line:84%
And when you take K steps
of your random walk,

00:06:15.030 --> 00:06:19.610 align:middle line:84%
you have a high probability
of being in this set.

00:06:19.610 --> 00:06:22.600 align:middle line:84%
And this set is sort of
like a group in this sense.

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:28.410 align:middle line:90%


00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:28.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:33.570 align:middle line:90%


00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:34.530 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:36.890 align:middle line:84%
And so there's
delta and epsilon.

00:06:36.890 --> 00:06:40.050 align:middle line:84%
Maybe at the beginning
I should say this.

00:06:40.050 --> 00:06:43.270 align:middle line:90%
And delta depends on epsilon.

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:44.110 align:middle line:90%
And it's positive.

00:06:44.110 --> 00:07:03.160 align:middle line:90%


00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:04.360 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:07:04.360 --> 00:07:07.190 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or
comments about theorem 1?

00:07:07.190 --> 00:07:10.536 align:middle line:84%
That's theorem 1, is Bourgain
and Gamburd, essentially.

00:07:10.536 --> 00:07:19.100 align:middle line:90%


00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:19.600 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:07:19.600 --> 00:07:23.487 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Where does the
A to the 2.5 come from?

00:07:23.487 --> 00:07:24.320 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:31.000 align:middle line:84%
So what's significant
here is just

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:38.760 align:middle line:84%
that this is significantly
smaller than the whole group.

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:45.160 align:middle line:90%
And if we-- yeah.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:47.600 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Does it equal
kind of a power on the side

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:48.440 align:middle line:90%
of [INAUDIBLE]?

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:56.315 align:middle line:90%


00:07:56.315 --> 00:07:57.190 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right.

00:07:57.190 --> 00:07:57.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:07:57.690 --> 00:07:59.370 align:middle line:84%
So this comes last
time from this--

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:02.230 align:middle line:90%


00:08:02.230 --> 00:08:04.730 align:middle line:84%
so actually, it's also important
that this is bigger than 2.

00:08:04.730 --> 00:08:12.920 align:middle line:84%
So we had this important
property of SL2(Fp), that it's--

00:08:12.920 --> 00:08:15.170 align:middle line:84%
ah yeah, so actually this
wouldn't work for any group.

00:08:15.170 --> 00:08:16.587 align:middle line:84%
So we have this
important property

00:08:16.587 --> 00:08:20.030 align:middle line:84%
for SL2(Fp) from last time, that
every non-trivial representation

00:08:20.030 --> 00:08:21.870 align:middle line:90%
has a large dimension.

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:26.710 align:middle line:84%
And that had the property that
if this thing had a small L2

00:08:26.710 --> 00:08:29.990 align:middle line:84%
norm, so it was kind of
decently well mixed, then

00:08:29.990 --> 00:08:31.333 align:middle line:90%
we would get a spectral gap.

00:08:31.333 --> 00:08:33.750 align:middle line:84%
And then if you kept going,
it would become really, really

00:08:33.750 --> 00:08:35.070 align:middle line:90%
well-mixed.

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:38.669 align:middle line:84%
And that's crucially
being used here.

00:08:38.669 --> 00:08:43.070 align:middle line:84%
And so here you could put
anything bigger than 2.

00:08:43.070 --> 00:08:47.070 align:middle line:84%
And the point is
that it can only

00:08:47.070 --> 00:08:50.300 align:middle line:84%
go wrong by getting stuck in
something of size really smaller

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:51.220 align:middle line:90%
than p squared.

00:08:51.220 --> 00:08:53.580 align:middle line:84%
Because we know once it's
spread over something of size

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:55.747 align:middle line:84%
bigger than p squared, then
it's going to keep going

00:08:55.747 --> 00:08:57.340 align:middle line:90%
and spread all the way.

00:08:57.340 --> 00:08:59.460 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, thanks.

00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:01.620 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:09:01.620 --> 00:09:02.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:02.660 --> 00:09:03.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:06.140 align:middle line:84%
Well, this theorem
raises a question.

00:09:06.140 --> 00:09:09.420 align:middle line:84%
Who are all the subsets
H that are like this?

00:09:09.420 --> 00:09:11.220 align:middle line:84%
It becomes a much
nicer theorem when

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:14.540 align:middle line:84%
we can write them
all down, or at least

00:09:14.540 --> 00:09:17.260 align:middle line:84%
say something
meaningful about them.

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:19.760 align:middle line:84%
So theorem 2' says
something about that.

00:09:19.760 --> 00:09:22.380 align:middle line:90%


00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:26.260 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is
due to Helfgott.

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:30.780 align:middle line:90%
And it builds on Hrushovski.

00:09:30.780 --> 00:09:35.140 align:middle line:90%


00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:35.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:44.660 align:middle line:84%
So it says if H is
a subset of SL2(Fp)

00:09:44.660 --> 00:09:53.120 align:middle line:84%
and it has these two
properties, so all of this stuff

00:09:53.120 --> 00:10:00.120 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than p to
the delta H. And H

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:02.540 align:middle line:90%
is at least p to the epsilon.

00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:04.140 align:middle line:90%
You can read that off from here.

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:07.480 align:middle line:84%
It's not going to get stuck
in something smaller than A.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:11.120 align:middle line:90%
And at most, p to the 2.5.

00:10:11.120 --> 00:10:15.760 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion is that H is
concentrated in a Borel subgroup

00:10:15.760 --> 00:10:17.280 align:middle line:90%
or Borel coset.

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:23.080 align:middle line:84%
So then there exists
a Borel subgroup B

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:28.240 align:middle line:84%
of an element g in our
group, so that H intersect

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:34.720 align:middle line:84%
B is bigger than some
small constant times H.

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:38.000 align:middle line:84%
So our approximate
subgroups basically have

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.360 align:middle line:90%
to sit in a Borel subgroup.

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:42.040 align:middle line:84%
This isn't a complete
classification

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:45.460 align:middle line:84%
because some of the subsets of
B are approximate subgroups,

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:48.190 align:middle line:84%
and many of them aren't,
but it's a meaningful piece

00:10:48.190 --> 00:10:49.090 align:middle line:90%
of information.

00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:52.590 align:middle line:90%


00:10:52.590 --> 00:10:53.790 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:57.110 align:middle line:84%
So you put these two
theorems together, you

00:10:57.110 --> 00:11:00.150 align:middle line:84%
can prove that theorem
pretty quickly.

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:02.030 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:11:02.030 --> 00:11:04.310 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: This C, does
it depend on anything,

00:11:04.310 --> 00:11:05.870 align:middle line:90%
or is it a universe?

00:11:05.870 --> 00:11:08.270 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Does
it depend on anything?

00:11:08.270 --> 00:11:09.370 align:middle line:90%
Let's put this here.

00:11:09.370 --> 00:11:12.590 align:middle line:90%


00:11:12.590 --> 00:11:13.330 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:11:13.330 --> 00:11:15.080 align:middle line:84%
I have all these
epsilons and deltas.

00:11:15.080 --> 00:11:18.910 align:middle line:90%


00:11:18.910 --> 00:11:21.070 align:middle line:84%
I don't think it
depends on anything.

00:11:21.070 --> 00:11:26.110 align:middle line:84%
So I guess here,
there should be this.

00:11:26.110 --> 00:11:27.870 align:middle line:90%
So we can do this.

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:30.510 align:middle line:84%
So this is getting stronger
as epsilon is getting smaller.

00:11:30.510 --> 00:11:34.630 align:middle line:84%
Epsilon is telling us that
our thing is not too small.

00:11:34.630 --> 00:11:39.452 align:middle line:84%
And then I think that
this is just a constant.

00:11:39.452 --> 00:11:41.910 align:middle line:84%
I guess that does suggest that
we could have said something

00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:43.090 align:middle line:90%
stronger up there.

00:11:43.090 --> 00:11:48.080 align:middle line:90%


00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:48.580 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:11:48.580 --> 00:11:55.855 align:middle line:90%


00:11:55.855 --> 00:12:04.100 align:middle line:84%
Oh, this is definitely H,
not B. I think it's right.

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:05.340 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:12:05.340 --> 00:12:07.400 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It's a question
about the choice of g.

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:11.260 align:middle line:84%
If the H is a symmetric
subset, would that kind of

00:12:11.260 --> 00:12:13.820 align:middle line:84%
imply that the
optimal g is always

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:15.240 align:middle line:90%
going to just be the identity?

00:12:15.240 --> 00:12:17.340 align:middle line:84%
Because you think of
H is kind of being

00:12:17.340 --> 00:12:18.966 align:middle line:90%
centered in some way around.

00:12:18.966 --> 00:12:24.260 align:middle line:84%
There would be some shifting
subgroup by kind of an identity

00:12:24.260 --> 00:12:26.947 align:middle line:84%
element, wouldn't
change the intersection?

00:12:26.947 --> 00:12:27.780 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:12:27.780 --> 00:12:31.480 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, maybe
if H were itself symmetric,

00:12:31.480 --> 00:12:34.420 align:middle line:84%
which in fact, I think
will happen in this setup,

00:12:34.420 --> 00:12:36.840 align:middle line:84%
then maybe you
don't need this g.

00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:39.660 align:middle line:84%
And maybe it's actually
only actual subgroups.

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:41.000 align:middle line:90%
I think that may be.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.990 align:middle line:84%
So let me just scribe that
I'm not sure we need g.

00:12:44.990 --> 00:13:07.810 align:middle line:90%


00:13:07.810 --> 00:13:08.676 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:13:08.676 --> 00:13:11.210 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so a good
example to think about

00:13:11.210 --> 00:13:15.050 align:middle line:84%
is if you just take a
coset of a Borel subgroup.

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:18.730 align:middle line:84%
And in the abelian world,
a coset of a subgroup

00:13:18.730 --> 00:13:22.490 align:middle line:84%
will be very small when
you add it to itself.

00:13:22.490 --> 00:13:26.810 align:middle line:84%
But in the non-abelian
world it's not so clear.

00:13:26.810 --> 00:13:29.090 align:middle line:90%
So I'll make a remark.

00:13:29.090 --> 00:13:34.570 align:middle line:84%
If H is a coset of
a Borel group, then

00:13:34.570 --> 00:13:37.090 align:middle line:90%
how big is just H times H?

00:13:37.090 --> 00:13:42.480 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's g times
B times g times B.

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:44.220 align:middle line:84%
And because it's
not commutative,

00:13:44.220 --> 00:13:47.320 align:middle line:90%
I can't bring this across.

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:50.220 align:middle line:84%
So it's not obvious
that this is small.

00:13:50.220 --> 00:13:51.820 align:middle line:84%
So I think this
is, in fact, large.

00:13:51.820 --> 00:13:59.840 align:middle line:90%


00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:04.000 align:middle line:84%
So based on that, I think it's
likely that we don't need this.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.890 align:middle line:84%
But it makes the proof
a little shorter.

00:14:06.890 --> 00:14:10.200 align:middle line:90%


00:14:10.200 --> 00:14:11.720 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:14:11.720 --> 00:14:15.800 align:middle line:84%
So I have a couple of
big-picture comments about this.

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:20.480 align:middle line:84%
One comment is let's compare
to the perhaps simpler

00:14:20.480 --> 00:14:22.600 align:middle line:90%
setting of an abelian group.

00:14:22.600 --> 00:14:24.880 align:middle line:84%
So maybe you have
the group of integers

00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:27.320 align:middle line:84%
or the group of
integers modulo p.

00:14:27.320 --> 00:14:29.360 align:middle line:84%
Suppose we had a
subset in there that

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:33.320 align:middle line:84%
had this property
and this property.

00:14:33.320 --> 00:14:35.560 align:middle line:84%
So when you add it
to itself, many times

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:38.240 align:middle line:84%
it expands, but only by a
little bit by a small power

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:40.080 align:middle line:90%
of the size of the set.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:43.150 align:middle line:84%
Then what can we say about
the structure of such things?

00:14:43.150 --> 00:14:47.190 align:middle line:84%
That's a big open problem
in additive combinatorics.

00:14:47.190 --> 00:14:50.430 align:middle line:84%
That's the
Freiman-Ruzsa problem.

00:14:50.430 --> 00:14:55.070 align:middle line:84%
If you have something even
smaller here, like log p or so,

00:14:55.070 --> 00:14:56.630 align:middle line:84%
then there would
be a classification

00:14:56.630 --> 00:14:58.870 align:middle line:84%
that would have to look like
a generalized arithmetic

00:14:58.870 --> 00:14:59.650 align:middle line:90%
progression.

00:14:59.650 --> 00:15:02.363 align:middle line:84%
But in this range,
there's not a whole lot.

00:15:02.363 --> 00:15:04.030 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing like
a structure theorem

00:15:04.030 --> 00:15:06.310 align:middle line:84%
that currently
exists in this range.

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:10.350 align:middle line:84%
So in a certain sense, this
is stronger information

00:15:10.350 --> 00:15:11.910 align:middle line:84%
in the non-commutative
world than we

00:15:11.910 --> 00:15:13.232 align:middle line:90%
have in the commutative world.

00:15:13.232 --> 00:15:15.190 align:middle line:84%
Of course, you might
point out that this is not

00:15:15.190 --> 00:15:17.390 align:middle line:84%
a complete structure
theorem either.

00:15:17.390 --> 00:15:18.950 align:middle line:84%
But this is a
really strong piece

00:15:18.950 --> 00:15:21.330 align:middle line:90%
of information about our group.

00:15:21.330 --> 00:15:23.430 align:middle line:84%
And I think in some
ways, it's stronger

00:15:23.430 --> 00:15:27.230 align:middle line:84%
than any of what we in
the commutative work.

00:15:27.230 --> 00:15:29.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:15:29.350 --> 00:15:31.110 align:middle line:90%
Another comment.

00:15:31.110 --> 00:15:31.850 align:middle line:90%
So I'm not sure.

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:34.630 align:middle line:84%
So Hrushovski and Heathcote
both worked on this.

00:15:34.630 --> 00:15:36.750 align:middle line:90%
Hrushovski came from logic.

00:15:36.750 --> 00:15:40.330 align:middle line:84%
And I think that he was
interested in the idea

00:15:40.330 --> 00:15:44.450 align:middle line:84%
from the point of view of logic
of an approximate subgroup,

00:15:44.450 --> 00:15:46.210 align:middle line:84%
like a basic thing
we have axioms

00:15:46.210 --> 00:15:48.450 align:middle line:84%
for is that the
axioms for a group

00:15:48.450 --> 00:15:51.870 align:middle line:84%
and what happens if you relax
those axioms a little bit?

00:15:51.870 --> 00:15:52.782 align:middle line:90%
What can you say?

00:15:52.782 --> 00:15:55.240 align:middle line:84%
So an interesting question from
the point of view of logic.

00:15:55.240 --> 00:15:58.090 align:middle line:90%


00:15:58.090 --> 00:15:59.650 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:15:59.650 --> 00:16:00.150 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:16:00.150 --> 00:16:02.890 align:middle line:84%
So the goal for the class is
to discuss each of these things

00:16:02.890 --> 00:16:06.560 align:middle line:84%
in moderate depth, probably
without giving complete proofs.

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:09.450 align:middle line:90%


00:16:09.450 --> 00:16:12.710 align:middle line:84%
And they have quite
different ideas.

00:16:12.710 --> 00:16:17.870 align:middle line:84%
But in both cases, the ideas are
related to stuff in our class.

00:16:17.870 --> 00:16:19.990 align:middle line:84%
So first, let's talk
about theorem 1.

00:16:19.990 --> 00:16:25.050 align:middle line:90%


00:16:25.050 --> 00:16:26.990 align:middle line:90%
So theorem 1.

00:16:26.990 --> 00:16:29.870 align:middle line:90%


00:16:29.870 --> 00:16:31.970 align:middle line:84%
So we start with the
measure mu, which

00:16:31.970 --> 00:16:39.160 align:middle line:84%
is mu A. And we notice
that mu L2 squared is

00:16:39.160 --> 00:16:40.800 align:middle line:90%
1 over the size of a.

00:16:40.800 --> 00:16:45.080 align:middle line:84%
So that's is at most p
to the minus epsilon.

00:16:45.080 --> 00:16:47.760 align:middle line:84%
Because it was built
into our assumptions here

00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:51.160 align:middle line:84%
that A is at least
p to the epsilon.

00:16:51.160 --> 00:16:53.920 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's start
convolving mu with itself.

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:55.920 align:middle line:84%
And we want to see if we
convolve it with itself

00:16:55.920 --> 00:17:00.200 align:middle line:84%
enough times is what will
happen to the L2 norm.

00:17:00.200 --> 00:17:03.360 align:middle line:90%
So let's say mu 2--

00:17:03.360 --> 00:17:05.359 align:middle line:90%
so that's called this mu 1.

00:17:05.359 --> 00:17:08.560 align:middle line:84%
Mu 2 is mu 1
convolved with mu 1.

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:13.060 align:middle line:84%
And in general, mu k plus 1
is mu k convolved with mu k.

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:15.579 align:middle line:84%
So we're convolving with this
thing with itself many times.

00:17:15.579 --> 00:17:18.900 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to see what
happens to the L2 norm.

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:25.200 align:middle line:84%
So recall that if
at some point mu k

00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:31.000 align:middle line:84%
L2 squared were to be smaller
than 1 over p to the 2.1, then

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:43.830 align:middle line:84%
we would get that sigma 1 of
T mu k was bounded by this.

00:17:43.830 --> 00:17:48.950 align:middle line:84%
And then we would get
that sigma 1 of T mu.

00:17:48.950 --> 00:17:53.630 align:middle line:84%
So mu k is mu convolved with
itself 2 to the k times.

00:17:53.630 --> 00:17:59.390 align:middle line:84%
So that would be p to the minus
1 over 10 times 2 to the k.

00:17:59.390 --> 00:18:02.790 align:middle line:84%
So if k is not too big, we
would get a spectral gap.

00:18:02.790 --> 00:18:03.670 align:middle line:90%
So that's our plan.

00:18:03.670 --> 00:18:06.175 align:middle line:90%


00:18:06.175 --> 00:18:07.550 align:middle line:84%
We keep doing
these convolutions,

00:18:07.550 --> 00:18:10.070 align:middle line:84%
and we watch what
happens to the L2 norm.

00:18:10.070 --> 00:18:13.750 align:middle line:84%
At every step, maybe the L2
norm goes down significantly.

00:18:13.750 --> 00:18:16.030 align:middle line:90%
In that case, we're happy.

00:18:16.030 --> 00:18:17.810 align:middle line:90%
Or maybe it doesn't go down.

00:18:17.810 --> 00:18:19.670 align:middle line:90%
In that case, we're stuck.

00:18:19.670 --> 00:18:22.950 align:middle line:84%
The stuck situation, we'll try
to analyze it carefully, and see

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:25.950 align:middle line:84%
that the stuck situation
only arises because

00:18:25.950 --> 00:18:29.110 align:middle line:90%
of this structure, this setup.

00:18:29.110 --> 00:18:32.070 align:middle line:90%
So let me write that out.

00:18:32.070 --> 00:18:35.070 align:middle line:84%
So let's say G
stands for our goal

00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:41.900 align:middle line:84%
all, which is that mu k
L2 squared is less than 1

00:18:41.900 --> 00:18:43.480 align:middle line:90%
over p to the 2.1.

00:18:43.480 --> 00:18:45.060 align:middle line:90%
If we get there, we're happy.

00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:48.900 align:middle line:90%
p will stand for progress.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:54.540 align:middle line:84%
We're not necessarily there,
but mu k plus 1 L2 squared

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:59.190 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by p to the
minus delta mu k L2 squared.

00:18:59.190 --> 00:19:03.960 align:middle line:90%


00:19:03.960 --> 00:19:08.100 align:middle line:84%
And then S stands
for stuck, which

00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:10.320 align:middle line:90%
means we're not at our goal.

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:13.340 align:middle line:90%
And we are not making progress.

00:19:13.340 --> 00:19:14.690 align:middle line:90%
Not goal and not progress.

00:19:14.690 --> 00:19:18.420 align:middle line:90%


00:19:18.420 --> 00:19:20.180 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:20.680 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:23.712 align:middle line:90%


00:19:23.712 --> 00:19:26.280 align:middle line:84%
So as long as we
don't get stuck,

00:19:26.280 --> 00:19:30.620 align:middle line:84%
we will reach our goal in
about over delta steps.

00:19:30.620 --> 00:19:40.650 align:middle line:84%
So if S never happens,
we reach the goal

00:19:40.650 --> 00:19:44.290 align:middle line:90%
and thus the over delta steps.

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:47.550 align:middle line:84%
And no matter what delta is,
delta is just a large constant.

00:19:47.550 --> 00:19:51.570 align:middle line:84%
And that is enough to
give the conclusion.

00:19:51.570 --> 00:19:55.250 align:middle line:84%
So then if you do a little
calculation using this,

00:19:55.250 --> 00:19:56.340 align:middle line:90%
you'll get a spectrum.

00:19:56.340 --> 00:20:06.010 align:middle line:90%


00:20:06.010 --> 00:20:09.610 align:middle line:84%
So suppose we do get
stuck, let's think

00:20:09.610 --> 00:20:10.640 align:middle line:90%
about what that means.

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:28.130 align:middle line:90%


00:20:28.130 --> 00:20:30.970 align:middle line:84%
So there was a comment at
the beginning of the class

00:20:30.970 --> 00:20:32.760 align:middle line:84%
that perhaps there's
not a big difference

00:20:32.760 --> 00:20:35.688 align:middle line:84%
between a set and a measure,
because if you have a set,

00:20:35.688 --> 00:20:36.980 align:middle line:90%
you can turn it into a measure.

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:39.640 align:middle line:84%
If you have a measure,
you can look at the points

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:43.480 align:middle line:84%
where the measure is pretty
big, and you get a set.

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:46.840 align:middle line:84%
And that's actually
what we're going to do.

00:20:46.840 --> 00:20:53.240 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that
A lambda of mu k

00:20:53.240 --> 00:20:56.440 align:middle line:84%
is the set of group
elements for our group

00:20:56.440 --> 00:21:02.840 align:middle line:84%
SL2 Fp, where mu k of g
is approximately lambda.

00:21:02.840 --> 00:21:05.640 align:middle line:84%
So we can decompose
our group into pieces

00:21:05.640 --> 00:21:07.680 align:middle line:90%
where mu k has various sizes.

00:21:07.680 --> 00:21:10.280 align:middle line:84%
And one of these sizes
must have a decent fraction

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:11.520 align:middle line:90%
of the measure.

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:23.320 align:middle line:84%
So we choose lambda so that
mu k of A lambda is around 1.

00:21:23.320 --> 00:21:26.120 align:middle line:84%
So we've cut our whole group
into maybe logarithmically

00:21:26.120 --> 00:21:27.120 align:middle line:90%
many pieces.

00:21:27.120 --> 00:21:28.660 align:middle line:90%
Their total measure is 1.

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:30.840 align:middle line:84%
So one of them has
to be pretty big.

00:21:30.840 --> 00:21:31.780 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:21:31.780 --> 00:21:35.640 align:middle line:84%
Now let's say Ak is
defined to be this set.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:39.460 align:middle line:90%


00:21:39.460 --> 00:21:43.980 align:middle line:84%
So what we've learned is that
mu k is roughly uniform on Ak.

00:21:43.980 --> 00:21:48.420 align:middle line:84%
And Ak has a good fraction
of the total measure of mu.

00:21:48.420 --> 00:21:49.170 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:21:49.170 --> 00:21:54.600 align:middle line:90%


00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:58.060 align:middle line:84%
So more or less, you could
imagine that mu k is just

00:21:58.060 --> 00:22:01.220 align:middle line:90%
the uniform measure on Ak.

00:22:01.220 --> 00:22:01.720 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:22:01.720 --> 00:22:03.700 align:middle line:84%
So now what would we
learn algebraically

00:22:03.700 --> 00:22:07.820 align:middle line:84%
about Ak from the fact
that we are stuck?

00:22:07.820 --> 00:22:09.460 align:middle line:84%
It actually has a
nice interpretation

00:22:09.460 --> 00:22:12.220 align:middle line:84%
in terms of a previous
character in our course, which

00:22:12.220 --> 00:22:14.820 align:middle line:90%
was the idea of energy.

00:22:14.820 --> 00:22:17.180 align:middle line:84%
So let's recall what
energy means and put it

00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:19.120 align:middle line:90%
in a non-commutative context.

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:22.000 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see that
it exactly fits here.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.900 align:middle line:90%


00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:31.330 align:middle line:84%
So let's say if we
have two subsets

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:37.050 align:middle line:84%
A and B in our group,
the energy of A, B

00:22:37.050 --> 00:22:43.352 align:middle line:90%
is the number of a1, a2, b1, b2.

00:22:43.352 --> 00:22:44.810 align:middle line:84%
These guys are in
A, and these guys

00:22:44.810 --> 00:22:51.540 align:middle line:84%
are in B, so that a1 times b1
is the same as a2 times b2.

00:22:51.540 --> 00:22:57.610 align:middle line:90%


00:22:57.610 --> 00:23:00.610 align:middle line:84%
Energy A, B. Now this
is the same definition

00:23:00.610 --> 00:23:03.850 align:middle line:84%
that we saw before in the
context of a commutative group.

00:23:03.850 --> 00:23:05.810 align:middle line:84%
Our group is now
not commutative,

00:23:05.810 --> 00:23:10.010 align:middle line:84%
which means that it matters what
order I wrote those things in.

00:23:10.010 --> 00:23:12.790 align:middle line:84%
And so it matters what order
I wrote those things in.

00:23:12.790 --> 00:23:16.850 align:middle line:84%
So E A, B is not actually
the same as E B, A.

00:23:16.850 --> 00:23:19.630 align:middle line:84%
But at least, otherwise it's a
very similar-looking definition.

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:27.330 align:middle line:90%


00:23:27.330 --> 00:23:31.080 align:middle line:84%
We can relate this
to this setup.

00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:34.760 align:middle line:90%
We can notice that E A, B is--

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:36.920 align:middle line:84%
I take the characteristic
function of A,

00:23:36.920 --> 00:23:40.520 align:middle line:84%
and I convolve it with the
characteristic function of B.

00:23:40.520 --> 00:23:43.060 align:middle line:84%
When I do that, If I
evaluate this at G,

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:45.400 align:middle line:84%
it will tell me how many
ways are there to write G

00:23:45.400 --> 00:23:48.120 align:middle line:90%
as little a times little b.

00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:50.080 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm going to
square it because I

00:23:50.080 --> 00:23:51.920 align:middle line:90%
want to have how many ways--

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:53.520 align:middle line:84%
I have that many
choices for this

00:23:53.520 --> 00:23:58.920 align:middle line:84%
and that many choices for that,
and sum over B. So this is this.

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:04.360 align:middle line:90%


00:24:04.360 --> 00:24:05.620 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:05.620 --> 00:24:08.580 align:middle line:90%
So notice I took something.

00:24:08.580 --> 00:24:11.760 align:middle line:84%
I convolved it by something
else, and I took its L2 norm.

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:15.190 align:middle line:84%
That's the character that's
involved in being stuck.

00:24:15.190 --> 00:24:21.240 align:middle line:90%


00:24:21.240 --> 00:24:22.910 align:middle line:90%
So something we can say.

00:24:22.910 --> 00:24:28.350 align:middle line:90%


00:24:28.350 --> 00:24:32.990 align:middle line:84%
Actually, before we do that, let
me make a little normalization.

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:33.640 align:middle line:90%
So remark.

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:36.550 align:middle line:90%


00:24:36.550 --> 00:24:44.390 align:middle line:84%
E A is in between A
cubed and A squared.

00:24:44.390 --> 00:24:46.190 align:middle line:90%
The A squared comes from--

00:24:46.190 --> 00:24:48.190 align:middle line:84%
I could take these
to be equal, and I

00:24:48.190 --> 00:24:50.590 align:middle line:90%
could take those to be equal.

00:24:50.590 --> 00:24:53.670 align:middle line:84%
And A cubed upper bound
comes from once I've

00:24:53.670 --> 00:24:55.950 align:middle line:84%
chosen these three,
there's at most

00:24:55.950 --> 00:24:59.670 align:middle line:90%
one choice for the last one.

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:03.090 align:middle line:84%
So these ones have a lot
of additive structure.

00:25:03.090 --> 00:25:05.910 align:middle line:84%
And the typical example
is an actual subgroup.

00:25:05.910 --> 00:25:12.310 align:middle line:84%
And these have very little
additive structure Now

00:25:12.310 --> 00:25:15.430 align:middle line:90%
let's relate to being stuck.

00:25:15.430 --> 00:25:25.860 align:middle line:84%
So if we are in the stuck case
for mu k, then we could see--

00:25:25.860 --> 00:25:27.560 align:middle line:84%
all right, I don't
want to write this.

00:25:27.560 --> 00:25:36.900 align:middle line:90%


00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:40.620 align:middle line:84%
So mu k is
essentially 1 over Ak,

00:25:40.620 --> 00:25:43.417 align:middle line:84%
its characteristic
function of Ak.

00:25:43.417 --> 00:25:45.000 align:middle line:84%
And if we want to
be rigorous, I guess

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:46.720 align:middle line:84%
we could say
something like this.

00:25:46.720 --> 00:25:49.580 align:middle line:90%


00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:57.740 align:middle line:84%
If we say mu k convolved
with mu k is larger than p

00:25:57.740 --> 00:26:06.660 align:middle line:84%
to the minus delta mu k,
this is equivalent to saying

00:26:06.660 --> 00:26:12.980 align:middle line:84%
that the energy, Ak with
Ak, is smaller than some p

00:26:12.980 --> 00:26:16.070 align:middle line:90%
to the delta times Ak cubed.

00:26:16.070 --> 00:26:18.900 align:middle line:90%


00:26:18.900 --> 00:26:23.460 align:middle line:84%
Claim if we unwind
this, we'll get this.

00:26:23.460 --> 00:26:28.890 align:middle line:84%
So we unwind this, we'll see
an energy, the energy of Ak.

00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:32.270 align:middle line:84%
This is almost the minimum
possible value of the L2 norm.

00:26:32.270 --> 00:26:34.690 align:middle line:90%
And so it's almost the--

00:26:34.690 --> 00:26:37.354 align:middle line:90%
sorry, it's almost the--

00:26:37.354 --> 00:26:39.210 align:middle line:90%
this goes the other way.

00:26:39.210 --> 00:26:42.390 align:middle line:90%
So let me say that again.

00:26:42.390 --> 00:26:44.490 align:middle line:90%
So this is encoding this energy.

00:26:44.490 --> 00:26:46.190 align:middle line:90%
It's a lower bound for it.

00:26:46.190 --> 00:26:52.610 align:middle line:84%
And the lower bound is almost
the biggest it could be.

00:26:52.610 --> 00:26:55.410 align:middle line:84%
So this energy is almost
the biggest it could be.

00:26:55.410 --> 00:26:56.130 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:26:56.130 --> 00:26:59.570 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: There could be a k
squared if it's a lower bound

00:26:59.570 --> 00:27:01.935 align:middle line:90%
for energy.

00:27:01.935 --> 00:27:02.810 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right.

00:27:02.810 --> 00:27:04.610 align:middle line:90%
No, it's Ak cubed.

00:27:04.610 --> 00:27:05.910 align:middle line:90%
And this is a minus sign.

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:06.910 align:middle line:90%
So this is possible.

00:27:06.910 --> 00:27:08.150 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:27:08.150 --> 00:27:12.410 align:middle line:90%
So this just got copied there.

00:27:12.410 --> 00:27:13.410 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:27:13.410 --> 00:27:15.250 align:middle line:84%
OK, so if you look
at this L2 norm,

00:27:15.250 --> 00:27:17.170 align:middle line:90%
these are probability measures.

00:27:17.170 --> 00:27:21.730 align:middle line:84%
So this L2 norm is
at most that L2 norm.

00:27:21.730 --> 00:27:23.670 align:middle line:84%
So when you look
at this inequality,

00:27:23.670 --> 00:27:26.710 align:middle line:90%
this L2 norm is really pinched.

00:27:26.710 --> 00:27:29.530 align:middle line:90%
It's at least a small fraction.

00:27:29.530 --> 00:27:31.790 align:middle line:84%
It's at least a large
fraction of mu L2 squared

00:27:31.790 --> 00:27:34.150 align:middle line:90%
and it's at most mu L2 squared.

00:27:34.150 --> 00:27:36.350 align:middle line:84%
So it's just about as
big as it could be.

00:27:36.350 --> 00:27:39.050 align:middle line:84%
So this energy is just
about as big as it could be.

00:27:39.050 --> 00:27:42.510 align:middle line:90%


00:27:42.510 --> 00:27:43.230 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:43.230 --> 00:27:44.790 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:27:44.790 --> 00:27:45.630 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:27:45.630 --> 00:27:53.070 align:middle line:84%
So if we get stuck, there must
be a subset of very high energy.

00:27:53.070 --> 00:27:59.050 align:middle line:84%
And that is a step towards
being an approximate subgroup.

00:27:59.050 --> 00:28:01.900 align:middle line:84%
But it's not as strong as
the conclusion of theorem 1.

00:28:01.900 --> 00:28:04.470 align:middle line:90%


00:28:04.470 --> 00:28:07.707 align:middle line:84%
So at this point, the story
connects to some characters

00:28:07.707 --> 00:28:09.790 align:middle line:84%
that we talked about when
we were doing projection

00:28:09.790 --> 00:28:12.190 align:middle line:90%
theory over finite fields.

00:28:12.190 --> 00:28:15.190 align:middle line:84%
It relates to the
Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers theorem

00:28:15.190 --> 00:28:17.430 align:middle line:84%
and the Plünnecke-Ruzsa
inequality.

00:28:17.430 --> 00:28:19.830 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, let me
just recall what they

00:28:19.830 --> 00:28:22.253 align:middle line:90%
said in the commutative case.

00:28:22.253 --> 00:28:23.920 align:middle line:84%
And then this is a
non-commutative case.

00:28:23.920 --> 00:28:25.700 align:middle line:84%
So then we'll have
to talk about what's

00:28:25.700 --> 00:28:27.480 align:middle line:84%
actually true in the
non-commutative case.

00:28:27.480 --> 00:28:31.100 align:middle line:90%


00:28:31.100 --> 00:28:38.300 align:middle line:84%
So recall that if we
have A contained in Z,

00:28:38.300 --> 00:28:48.980 align:middle line:84%
a commutative group, then we
have two important theorems,

00:28:48.980 --> 00:28:50.980 align:middle line:90%
Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers.

00:28:50.980 --> 00:28:58.660 align:middle line:84%
Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers says
that if A has a lot of energy,

00:28:58.660 --> 00:29:00.470 align:middle line:90%
then it has a large subset.

00:29:00.470 --> 00:29:07.340 align:middle line:90%


00:29:07.340 --> 00:29:11.690 align:middle line:84%
And the large subset
actually has a small subset.

00:29:11.690 --> 00:29:18.220 align:middle line:90%


00:29:18.220 --> 00:29:23.730 align:middle line:84%
So this set has added a
structure in one sense,

00:29:23.730 --> 00:29:25.650 align:middle line:84%
but it has a large
subset which has added

00:29:25.650 --> 00:29:28.770 align:middle line:90%
structure in a stronger sense.

00:29:28.770 --> 00:29:31.250 align:middle line:90%
And then once we have this--

00:29:31.250 --> 00:29:35.050 align:middle line:84%
so another important theorem,
the Plünnecke-Ruzsa theorem that

00:29:35.050 --> 00:29:40.810 align:middle line:84%
says if A prime plus A prime,
smaller than L times A prime--

00:29:40.810 --> 00:29:43.450 align:middle line:90%
so L will be this--

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:46.270 align:middle line:84%
then you can also look at
the sum of three of them,

00:29:46.270 --> 00:29:47.850 align:middle line:90%
or four of them, or whatever.

00:29:47.850 --> 00:29:58.065 align:middle line:84%
So I'll just write this guy
is bounded by L to the 5th.

00:29:58.065 --> 00:29:59.190 align:middle line:90%
You could put other things.

00:29:59.190 --> 00:29:59.990 align:middle line:90%
You get the idea.

00:29:59.990 --> 00:30:04.690 align:middle line:90%


00:30:04.690 --> 00:30:06.810 align:middle line:84%
This sequence of
theorems is important

00:30:06.810 --> 00:30:10.650 align:middle line:84%
because it gives
amplification of structure.

00:30:10.650 --> 00:30:14.930 align:middle line:84%
So this assumption is that A
has some additive structure

00:30:14.930 --> 00:30:18.170 align:middle line:90%
and some fairly weak sense.

00:30:18.170 --> 00:30:21.400 align:middle line:84%
And that implies that a big
subset has additive structure

00:30:21.400 --> 00:30:23.160 align:middle line:90%
in a stronger sense.

00:30:23.160 --> 00:30:25.120 align:middle line:84%
And then therefore, it
has additive structure

00:30:25.120 --> 00:30:26.190 align:middle line:90%
in even stronger sense.

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:30.800 align:middle line:90%


00:30:30.800 --> 00:30:33.880 align:middle line:84%
So if we were allowed to just
apply these two theorems, then

00:30:33.880 --> 00:30:36.740 align:middle line:84%
from this moment, we would get
the conclusion of theorem 1.

00:30:36.740 --> 00:30:38.532 align:middle line:84%
Conclusion of theorem
1 would be that there

00:30:38.532 --> 00:30:44.740 align:middle line:84%
is some set H, which could
have been Ak, which obeys this.

00:30:44.740 --> 00:30:51.520 align:middle line:90%


00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:54.258 align:middle line:84%
We can't do that because this
is for a commutative group.

00:30:54.258 --> 00:30:55.800 align:middle line:84%
So we need to talk
about what happens

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:57.960 align:middle line:90%
in a non-commutative group.

00:30:57.960 --> 00:31:00.343 align:middle line:90%
But I thought it was--

00:31:00.343 --> 00:31:01.260 align:middle line:90%
we'll talk about that.

00:31:01.260 --> 00:31:04.120 align:middle line:84%
But I also thought it was a nice
moment to recall these theorems

00:31:04.120 --> 00:31:08.080 align:middle line:84%
and really appreciate that
they're important and useful

00:31:08.080 --> 00:31:09.780 align:middle line:90%
and do something kind of neat.

00:31:09.780 --> 00:31:15.240 align:middle line:90%


00:31:15.240 --> 00:31:17.440 align:middle line:84%
Halfway through the
course, check-in email.

00:31:17.440 --> 00:31:20.610 align:middle line:84%
When I asked people
what things that we did,

00:31:20.610 --> 00:31:23.310 align:middle line:84%
do you feel like they really
sunk in and you understood them

00:31:23.310 --> 00:31:26.110 align:middle line:84%
and what things would feel
it was maybe hard to remember

00:31:26.110 --> 00:31:28.030 align:middle line:90%
what actually was happening?

00:31:28.030 --> 00:31:30.990 align:middle line:84%
this theorem in particular
was cited as something

00:31:30.990 --> 00:31:32.030 align:middle line:90%
where it was hard--

00:31:32.030 --> 00:31:34.870 align:middle line:84%
people did not feel like they
remembered very well what

00:31:34.870 --> 00:31:37.950 align:middle line:90%
actually happened.

00:31:37.950 --> 00:31:41.010 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we get to
talk about it again.

00:31:41.010 --> 00:31:41.510 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:31:41.510 --> 00:31:43.950 align:middle line:90%


00:31:43.950 --> 00:31:44.450 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:44.450 --> 00:31:46.650 align:middle line:84%
Oh, I guess another thing
you might wonder is,

00:31:46.650 --> 00:31:49.050 align:middle line:84%
OK, this logically is
stronger than this,

00:31:49.050 --> 00:31:50.290 align:middle line:90%
but does it really matter.

00:31:50.290 --> 00:31:52.850 align:middle line:84%
Later when we look at theorem
2, we'll have a good example.

00:31:52.850 --> 00:31:55.812 align:middle line:84%
Theorem 2 really requires
this as an input.

00:31:55.812 --> 00:31:57.270 align:middle line:84%
So we'll see an
interesting example

00:31:57.270 --> 00:31:58.530 align:middle line:90%
of why you might want this.

00:31:58.530 --> 00:32:06.350 align:middle line:90%


00:32:06.350 --> 00:32:09.260 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about the
Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers theorem.

00:32:09.260 --> 00:32:12.750 align:middle line:90%


00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:13.848 align:middle line:90%
So I will tell you--

00:32:13.848 --> 00:32:15.390 align:middle line:84%
yeah, I guess first
I should tell you

00:32:15.390 --> 00:32:17.460 align:middle line:84%
what is true in the
non-commutative world, which

00:32:17.460 --> 00:32:20.060 align:middle line:84%
really looks pretty
similar to this.

00:32:20.060 --> 00:32:23.700 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll actually
remember the proof a little bit

00:32:23.700 --> 00:32:26.650 align:middle line:84%
to see if we can get the proof
to sink in a little bit deeper.

00:32:26.650 --> 00:32:34.760 align:middle line:90%


00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:35.260 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:35.260 --> 00:32:37.960 align:middle line:90%


00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:39.560 align:middle line:90%
So I'm going to erase this.

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:42.300 align:middle line:84%
And what I want us to remember
is just that to finish theorem

00:32:42.300 --> 00:32:44.460 align:middle line:84%
1, what we need
is a good version

00:32:44.460 --> 00:32:47.340 align:middle line:84%
of Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers
and Plünnecke-Ruzsa

00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:48.800 align:middle line:90%
in the non-commutative world.

00:32:48.800 --> 00:33:10.700 align:middle line:90%


00:33:10.700 --> 00:33:13.460 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:33:13.460 --> 00:33:15.740 align:middle line:90%
So theorem.

00:33:15.740 --> 00:33:21.400 align:middle line:84%
Non-commutative
Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers.

00:33:21.400 --> 00:33:29.000 align:middle line:84%
It says if A is a subset of
a group, G, and the energy

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:35.720 align:middle line:84%
A A is at least k
inverse A cubed,

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:40.200 align:middle line:84%
then there exists a
subset A prime in A

00:33:40.200 --> 00:33:41.700 align:middle line:90%
so that it's pretty big.

00:33:41.700 --> 00:33:46.920 align:middle line:90%


00:33:46.920 --> 00:33:49.160 align:middle line:84%
And there are a few
different things

00:33:49.160 --> 00:33:53.810 align:middle line:84%
we could write, but actually,
let me call this A tilde.

00:33:53.810 --> 00:33:56.600 align:middle line:90%


00:33:56.600 --> 00:34:00.460 align:middle line:84%
A tilde times A tilde
inverse is not too big.

00:34:00.460 --> 00:34:12.679 align:middle line:90%


00:34:12.679 --> 00:34:14.340 align:middle line:90%
It looks very little different.

00:34:14.340 --> 00:34:24.870 align:middle line:90%


00:34:24.870 --> 00:34:27.150 align:middle line:84%
But let's take this
opportunity to remember

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:29.949 align:middle line:84%
how the proof worked, and
see if we can get it to sink

00:34:29.949 --> 00:34:32.870 align:middle line:90%
in a little bit more deeply.

00:34:32.870 --> 00:34:34.139 align:middle line:90%
All right, so proof sketch.

00:34:34.139 --> 00:34:39.429 align:middle line:90%


00:34:39.429 --> 00:34:41.310 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:34:41.310 --> 00:34:47.150 align:middle line:84%
So remember that the energy A A
is the sum over all of our group

00:34:47.150 --> 00:34:55.909 align:middle line:84%
elements of r A A of G
squared, where r A A of G

00:34:55.909 --> 00:35:03.810 align:middle line:84%
is the number of pairs a1, a2
squared so that a1 a2 is g.

00:35:03.810 --> 00:35:06.350 align:middle line:90%


00:35:06.350 --> 00:35:07.350 align:middle line:90%
That's the energy.

00:35:07.350 --> 00:35:09.870 align:middle line:84%
So for the energy
to be large, there

00:35:09.870 --> 00:35:14.140 align:middle line:84%
must be a lot of group elements
g, where this is pretty large.

00:35:14.140 --> 00:35:16.150 align:middle line:84%
We'll call those
popular products.

00:35:16.150 --> 00:35:24.820 align:middle line:90%


00:35:24.820 --> 00:35:30.320 align:middle line:84%
So p, the set of
popular products.

00:35:30.320 --> 00:35:35.500 align:middle line:84%
This is the set of g, where
r A A of G is greater than k

00:35:35.500 --> 00:35:40.035 align:middle line:84%
to the minus something times
the size of A. So the size of A

00:35:40.035 --> 00:35:41.160 align:middle line:90%
is the biggest it could be.

00:35:41.160 --> 00:35:43.388 align:middle line:84%
And so they're almost
as big as it could be.

00:35:43.388 --> 00:35:44.430 align:middle line:90%
So they're quite popular.

00:35:44.430 --> 00:35:48.780 align:middle line:90%


00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:49.280 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:35:49.280 --> 00:35:52.460 align:middle line:84%
So it's an exercise to see that
if the energy is really big,

00:35:52.460 --> 00:35:55.110 align:middle line:84%
most of the energy actually
comes from popular products.

00:35:55.110 --> 00:35:59.260 align:middle line:90%


00:35:59.260 --> 00:36:03.620 align:middle line:90%
Energy A A is pretty much as--

00:36:03.620 --> 00:36:06.220 align:middle line:90%
it's more than 1/2 comes from.

00:36:06.220 --> 00:36:10.540 align:middle line:84%
So 1/2 of the energy of A
is less than the sum over g

00:36:10.540 --> 00:36:18.090 align:middle line:84%
in the popular
products of r A A of G.

00:36:18.090 --> 00:36:19.610 align:middle line:84%
If this is having
popular products,

00:36:19.610 --> 00:36:21.852 align:middle line:84%
that's almost equivalent
to having a lot of energy.

00:36:21.852 --> 00:36:23.310 align:middle line:84%
Those are basically
the same thing.

00:36:23.310 --> 00:36:25.850 align:middle line:90%


00:36:25.850 --> 00:36:27.250 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:36:27.250 --> 00:36:29.610 align:middle line:84%
So then we'll do a little
thought experiment.

00:36:29.610 --> 00:36:33.370 align:middle line:84%
Suppose that every
product was popular.

00:36:33.370 --> 00:36:35.530 align:middle line:84%
Every product in
the product set of A

00:36:35.530 --> 00:36:38.630 align:middle line:84%
had the same number
of representations.

00:36:38.630 --> 00:36:40.130 align:middle line:84%
Well, that number
of representations

00:36:40.130 --> 00:36:43.250 align:middle line:84%
would have to be pretty large
because there's a lot of energy.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:45.900 align:middle line:84%
And that would tell us
that A times A was small.

00:36:45.900 --> 00:36:50.020 align:middle line:90%


00:36:50.020 --> 00:36:53.450 align:middle line:84%
So then we would be done,
and A tilde could just be A.

00:36:53.450 --> 00:36:55.890 align:middle line:84%
But that's not true
because it's not true

00:36:55.890 --> 00:36:58.010 align:middle line:84%
that every element
can be written

00:36:58.010 --> 00:37:00.070 align:middle line:84%
as a product in the
same number of ways.

00:37:00.070 --> 00:37:03.090 align:middle line:90%


00:37:03.090 --> 00:37:04.970 align:middle line:84%
So what we want to
do, we're hoping

00:37:04.970 --> 00:37:08.450 align:middle line:84%
to find a subset, A
tilde, so that all

00:37:08.450 --> 00:37:10.360 align:middle line:90%
the products in A tilde--

00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:12.520 align:middle line:84%
A tilde times A
tilde-- they all can

00:37:12.520 --> 00:37:17.080 align:middle line:84%
be written as a product
in lots of ways,

00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:20.540 align:middle line:90%
or something in that sphere.

00:37:20.540 --> 00:37:23.570 align:middle line:84%
So now let's make the
popular product to graph.

00:37:23.570 --> 00:37:32.000 align:middle line:90%


00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.880 align:middle line:84%
So the vertices are
G cross G, there's

00:37:34.880 --> 00:37:40.240 align:middle line:84%
a copy of G.
There's a copy of G.

00:37:40.240 --> 00:37:47.240 align:middle line:84%
And we put an edge
from A to B. So

00:37:47.240 --> 00:37:53.570 align:middle line:84%
edge from A to B if a times
B is a popular product.

00:37:53.570 --> 00:37:59.960 align:middle line:90%


00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:01.700 align:middle line:84%
Actually, this is
not a G by G graph.

00:38:01.700 --> 00:38:04.680 align:middle line:84%
This is an A by A graph,
taking elements of our set

00:38:04.680 --> 00:38:07.400 align:middle line:90%
and looking at their products.

00:38:07.400 --> 00:38:09.730 align:middle line:84%
Not every pair is
a popular product.

00:38:09.730 --> 00:38:13.483 align:middle line:84%
They might not all be popular,
but there are by hypothesis,

00:38:13.483 --> 00:38:15.150 align:middle line:84%
because there's a lot
of energy, there's

00:38:15.150 --> 00:38:16.990 align:middle line:90%
a lot of popular products.

00:38:16.990 --> 00:38:19.540 align:middle line:84%
So the number of
edges is at least--

00:38:19.540 --> 00:38:22.190 align:middle line:90%


00:38:22.190 --> 00:38:23.810 align:middle line:84%
there are lots of
edges in this graph.

00:38:23.810 --> 00:38:35.150 align:middle line:90%


00:38:35.150 --> 00:38:39.390 align:middle line:84%
A tilde is going to be
some subset over here.

00:38:39.390 --> 00:38:47.750 align:middle line:84%
And the good feature of A tilde
is that for every a1 and a2

00:38:47.750 --> 00:38:51.370 align:middle line:84%
both in A tilde,
there are many edges--

00:38:51.370 --> 00:38:52.490 align:middle line:90%
there are many paths.

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:53.850 align:middle line:90%
So let me draw it.

00:38:53.850 --> 00:39:00.390 align:middle line:90%


00:39:00.390 --> 00:39:04.110 align:middle line:84%
So let's say this is
a1 and this is a2.

00:39:04.110 --> 00:39:07.930 align:middle line:84%
And then we're going to
think of paths of length 4

00:39:07.930 --> 00:39:11.950 align:middle line:90%
that go from a1 to a2.

00:39:11.950 --> 00:39:14.890 align:middle line:90%


00:39:14.890 --> 00:39:25.930 align:middle line:84%
So there are many or more than
something paths of length 4

00:39:25.930 --> 00:39:28.680 align:middle line:84%
that go from a1 to
a2 in our graph.

00:39:28.680 --> 00:39:32.920 align:middle line:90%


00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:34.250 align:middle line:90%
And how many?

00:39:34.250 --> 00:39:37.930 align:middle line:84%
Well, from a
typical point, there

00:39:37.930 --> 00:39:45.050 align:middle line:84%
are about maybe 1 over
k times A edges out.

00:39:45.050 --> 00:39:51.710 align:middle line:84%
And so we have A choices,
A choices, A choices.

00:39:51.710 --> 00:39:53.070 align:middle line:90%
And then we have to go to a2.

00:39:53.070 --> 00:40:06.090 align:middle line:90%


00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:08.760 align:middle line:84%
There was a graph
theory lemma that we

00:40:08.760 --> 00:40:11.920 align:middle line:84%
can choose a substantial
set, A tilde, here that

00:40:11.920 --> 00:40:14.200 align:middle line:90%
has all of these edges.

00:40:14.200 --> 00:40:16.240 align:middle line:84%
That was the hardest
part of the proof,

00:40:16.240 --> 00:40:17.940 align:middle line:84%
but it's exactly
the same as before.

00:40:17.940 --> 00:40:20.480 align:middle line:84%
It had nothing to do with
anything being commutative.

00:40:20.480 --> 00:40:25.080 align:middle line:90%
So at that part, I won't repeat.

00:40:25.080 --> 00:40:33.000 align:middle line:84%
So there was a lemma that
we can choose A tilde.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:35.360 align:middle line:90%
So this is true.

00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:37.060 align:middle line:90%
And A tilde is pretty big.

00:40:37.060 --> 00:40:46.020 align:middle line:90%


00:40:46.020 --> 00:40:46.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:50.800 align:middle line:90%


00:40:50.800 --> 00:40:52.680 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:40:52.680 --> 00:40:56.310 align:middle line:84%
So let's name everybody
in the middle here.

00:40:56.310 --> 00:40:59.800 align:middle line:90%


00:40:59.800 --> 00:41:01.400 align:middle line:90%
I name these.

00:41:01.400 --> 00:41:03.190 align:middle line:90%
Let me actually rename these.

00:41:03.190 --> 00:41:07.390 align:middle line:90%


00:41:07.390 --> 00:41:14.350 align:middle line:84%
I'll call these
A. A and A prime.

00:41:14.350 --> 00:41:20.870 align:middle line:84%
And then we go over
here to a1 to a2 to a3.

00:41:20.870 --> 00:41:23.630 align:middle line:90%
So we know a a1 is popular.

00:41:23.630 --> 00:41:25.890 align:middle line:90%
We know a2 times a1 is popular.

00:41:25.890 --> 00:41:28.890 align:middle line:84%
We know a2 times a3
is popular, and so on.

00:41:28.890 --> 00:41:34.510 align:middle line:90%


00:41:34.510 --> 00:41:39.630 align:middle line:84%
What this allows us to do
is to write A over A prime

00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:40.820 align:middle line:90%
in many different ways.

00:41:40.820 --> 00:41:45.910 align:middle line:90%


00:41:45.910 --> 00:41:48.725 align:middle line:84%
a over-- I have to be
careful because I'm

00:41:48.725 --> 00:41:49.850 align:middle line:90%
in a non-commutative group.

00:41:49.850 --> 00:41:51.590 align:middle line:90%
I think I want to write a.

00:41:51.590 --> 00:41:58.750 align:middle line:84%
Let's call this a tilde
a times a tilde inverse.

00:41:58.750 --> 00:42:02.470 align:middle line:90%
So that's a times a1.

00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:07.660 align:middle line:84%
And now I'll put a2
times a1 inverse.

00:42:07.660 --> 00:42:11.340 align:middle line:90%
And now I'll put a2 times a3.

00:42:11.340 --> 00:42:16.710 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll put a
tilde times a3 inverse.

00:42:16.710 --> 00:42:19.940 align:middle line:90%


00:42:19.940 --> 00:42:23.380 align:middle line:90%
So if we do this out--

00:42:23.380 --> 00:42:28.740 align:middle line:84%
so this guy here is
a1 inverse a2 inverse.

00:42:28.740 --> 00:42:32.980 align:middle line:84%
You can see cancelation,
cancelation.

00:42:32.980 --> 00:42:37.780 align:middle line:84%
And this guy here is a3
inverse, a tilde inverse.

00:42:37.780 --> 00:42:39.020 align:middle line:90%
Cancel that.

00:42:39.020 --> 00:42:40.160 align:middle line:90%
So that's this equality.

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:43.620 align:middle line:84%
It's not difficult.
But we've written it

00:42:43.620 --> 00:42:46.070 align:middle line:84%
in terms of four guys
that are popular.

00:42:46.070 --> 00:42:48.620 align:middle line:90%


00:42:48.620 --> 00:42:54.120 align:middle line:84%
So this a2 times a1 is
not just a2 times a1,

00:42:54.120 --> 00:42:55.520 align:middle line:90%
it's a popular product.

00:42:55.520 --> 00:42:58.820 align:middle line:84%
It can be written in
many different ways.

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:12.370 align:middle line:84%
So a times a tilde inverse can
be written as z1, z2 inverse--

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:21.260 align:middle line:84%
or maybe p1, p2 inverse, p3, p4
inverse, where pi are popular.

00:43:21.260 --> 00:43:33.370 align:middle line:90%


00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:35.280 align:middle line:84%
This can be done in
many different ways.

00:43:35.280 --> 00:43:40.630 align:middle line:90%


00:43:40.630 --> 00:43:48.860 align:middle line:84%
And the number of choices for
the pi is at least A cubed.

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:51.470 align:middle line:90%


00:43:51.470 --> 00:43:53.650 align:middle line:84%
So the conclusion
is that the size

00:43:53.650 --> 00:43:58.370 align:middle line:84%
of A tilde times A tilde
inverse is bounded by--

00:43:58.370 --> 00:44:00.710 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to choose
four popular guys.

00:44:00.710 --> 00:44:02.960 align:middle line:90%
So that's p to the 4th.

00:44:02.960 --> 00:44:07.320 align:middle line:84%
And then I have overcounted,
because each person has now

00:44:07.320 --> 00:44:10.520 align:middle line:84%
been represented A
cubed different ways,

00:44:10.520 --> 00:44:14.520 align:middle line:90%
and ignoring some factors of k.

00:44:14.520 --> 00:44:27.080 align:middle line:90%
And so that's A. OK.

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:36.093 align:middle line:90%


00:44:36.093 --> 00:44:37.760 align:middle line:84%
So I remember the
first time I taught it

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:41.760 align:middle line:84%
I struggled a little bit
with the intuition of this.

00:44:41.760 --> 00:44:45.360 align:middle line:84%
The first thing you might hope
to do is to choose A tilde,

00:44:45.360 --> 00:44:49.965 align:middle line:84%
so that every product in
A tilde can be is popular.

00:44:49.965 --> 00:44:51.840 align:middle line:84%
They all can be written
in many ways, just as

00:44:51.840 --> 00:44:53.640 align:middle line:84%
a product of two
things in A. And then

00:44:53.640 --> 00:44:55.800 align:middle line:84%
there are clearly
not so many of those.

00:44:55.800 --> 00:44:58.260 align:middle line:84%
But I think it's not
possible to do that.

00:44:58.260 --> 00:44:59.965 align:middle line:84%
It's not possible
to choose A tilde

00:44:59.965 --> 00:45:01.340 align:middle line:84%
where every one
of these products

00:45:01.340 --> 00:45:04.380 align:middle line:90%
is popular in that sense.

00:45:04.380 --> 00:45:07.960 align:middle line:84%
But by being a little
bit more flexible,

00:45:07.960 --> 00:45:12.020 align:middle line:84%
we've chosen A tilde so
that every quotient can

00:45:12.020 --> 00:45:15.300 align:middle line:84%
be written in many
ways, not just

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:16.740 align:middle line:84%
as a quotient of
two things in A,

00:45:16.740 --> 00:45:21.080 align:middle line:84%
but many ways in this slightly
more flexible framework.

00:45:21.080 --> 00:45:24.580 align:middle line:90%


00:45:24.580 --> 00:45:26.170 align:middle line:90%
Any questions or comments?

00:45:26.170 --> 00:45:30.740 align:middle line:90%


00:45:30.740 --> 00:45:32.580 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:45:32.580 --> 00:45:37.780 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So why can't you get
the same result for A times A

00:45:37.780 --> 00:45:40.123 align:middle line:84%
if you just choose
paths of length 3?

00:45:40.123 --> 00:45:42.540 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, I think
you could get the same result

00:45:42.540 --> 00:45:44.980 align:middle line:84%
for A times A if you
choose paths of length 3

00:45:44.980 --> 00:45:48.520 align:middle line:90%
or A times B. Yeah.

00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:50.860 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, I maybe was not
transparent about--

00:45:50.860 --> 00:45:54.820 align:middle line:84%
so the thing with paths
of length 3 still works.

00:45:54.820 --> 00:45:58.690 align:middle line:84%
I think that might produce
two different subsets.

00:45:58.690 --> 00:46:00.470 align:middle line:84%
Actually, maybe in
the commutative case,

00:46:00.470 --> 00:46:02.512 align:middle line:84%
I actually should have
had two different subsets.

00:46:02.512 --> 00:46:05.130 align:middle line:90%


00:46:05.130 --> 00:46:06.850 align:middle line:90%
At least initially.

00:46:06.850 --> 00:46:08.570 align:middle line:90%
It works fine.

00:46:08.570 --> 00:46:11.030 align:middle line:84%
The reason that I have A
tilde times A tilde inverse,

00:46:11.030 --> 00:46:13.408 align:middle line:84%
the motivation for that is
going to come in a moment.

00:46:13.408 --> 00:46:15.450 align:middle line:84%
And actually, I'm going
to try to argue that this

00:46:15.450 --> 00:46:18.730 align:middle line:90%
is better than A times A.

00:46:18.730 --> 00:46:20.670 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And just
to clarify anything,

00:46:20.670 --> 00:46:23.250 align:middle line:84%
the way you stated it before
the popular products here

00:46:23.250 --> 00:46:28.890 align:middle line:84%
is the subset of A times A,
with the small projection.

00:46:28.890 --> 00:46:32.530 align:middle line:84%
Because it was stated in
terms of a subset having

00:46:32.530 --> 00:46:36.730 align:middle line:84%
a large projection,
then that leads to--

00:46:36.730 --> 00:46:43.013 align:middle line:84%
you can choose A subset of
such that the subset is small.

00:46:43.013 --> 00:46:44.430 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH:
Yeah, that's right.

00:46:44.430 --> 00:46:44.972 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:46:44.972 --> 00:46:46.650 align:middle line:84%
So in the projection
theory version,

00:46:46.650 --> 00:46:49.190 align:middle line:84%
this would be the
small projection.

00:46:49.190 --> 00:46:52.970 align:middle line:84%
And there'd be some big piece
of A cross A that projects here.

00:46:52.970 --> 00:46:55.250 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, thanks.

00:46:55.250 --> 00:46:56.410 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:46:56.410 --> 00:46:57.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:57.680 --> 00:46:59.060 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:46:59.060 --> 00:47:00.960 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
non-commutative analog

00:47:00.960 --> 00:47:02.880 align:middle line:90%
of Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers.

00:47:02.880 --> 00:47:05.640 align:middle line:84%
It really looks a lot like
Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers.

00:47:05.640 --> 00:47:08.100 align:middle line:84%
And this inverse is
because we want it.

00:47:08.100 --> 00:47:11.080 align:middle line:84%
We probably could also have
had A tilde times B tilde

00:47:11.080 --> 00:47:11.780 align:middle line:90%
if we wanted.

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:14.512 align:middle line:90%


00:47:14.512 --> 00:47:16.960 align:middle line:84%
The situation with
Plünnecke-Ruzsa is actually

00:47:16.960 --> 00:47:18.780 align:middle line:90%
a little bit more complicated.

00:47:18.780 --> 00:47:38.120 align:middle line:90%


00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:40.245 align:middle line:90%
So non-commutative.

00:47:40.245 --> 00:47:44.000 align:middle line:90%


00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:44.920 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:47:44.920 --> 00:47:46.860 align:middle line:90%
So let's ask a question.

00:47:46.860 --> 00:47:50.080 align:middle line:84%
Suppose we have is A
as a subset of a group,

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:52.030 align:middle line:90%
and A times A is small.

00:47:52.030 --> 00:47:55.160 align:middle line:90%


00:47:55.160 --> 00:47:59.180 align:middle line:84%
Does it imply that A
times A times A is small?

00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:04.710 align:middle line:90%


00:48:04.710 --> 00:48:06.550 align:middle line:84%
So this would be
that natural analog

00:48:06.550 --> 00:48:08.350 align:middle line:90%
of Plünnecke's inequality.

00:48:08.350 --> 00:48:10.880 align:middle line:90%
And the answer to this is no.

00:48:10.880 --> 00:48:13.910 align:middle line:90%


00:48:13.910 --> 00:48:17.070 align:middle line:90%
OK, here's the example.

00:48:17.070 --> 00:48:21.270 align:middle line:84%
So let's say H contained
in G is a subgroup.

00:48:21.270 --> 00:48:25.450 align:middle line:84%
And A is H union
one other element,

00:48:25.450 --> 00:48:27.910 align:middle line:90%
which is not in the subgroup.

00:48:27.910 --> 00:48:31.760 align:middle line:84%
Now what happens when
I take A times A?

00:48:31.760 --> 00:48:36.920 align:middle line:84%
A times A is H times
H-- that's good--

00:48:36.920 --> 00:48:44.830 align:middle line:84%
plus, or union, H times g union
g times H union g times g.

00:48:44.830 --> 00:48:46.370 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing
special about these.

00:48:46.370 --> 00:48:48.670 align:middle line:84%
But because g is only one
element, all of this stuff

00:48:48.670 --> 00:48:50.430 align:middle line:90%
is small.

00:48:50.430 --> 00:48:54.070 align:middle line:84%
So we can see that A
times A is smaller than--

00:48:54.070 --> 00:48:57.700 align:middle line:84%
1, 2, 3-- it's smaller
than 4A, probably 3A.

00:48:57.700 --> 00:49:01.620 align:middle line:90%


00:49:01.620 --> 00:49:07.460 align:middle line:84%
But now what happens when
I take A times A times A?

00:49:07.460 --> 00:49:09.620 align:middle line:90%
OK, now I have three factors.

00:49:09.620 --> 00:49:16.900 align:middle line:84%
And so that concludes
H times g times H.

00:49:16.900 --> 00:49:21.260 align:middle line:84%
In the non-commutative world,
I cannot slide this over.

00:49:21.260 --> 00:49:23.040 align:middle line:90%
And this is not so good.

00:49:23.040 --> 00:49:25.940 align:middle line:84%
There is no reason
for this to be small.

00:49:25.940 --> 00:49:30.860 align:middle line:84%
And so the size of
H times g times H

00:49:30.860 --> 00:49:34.910 align:middle line:84%
could well be the
size of H squared.

00:49:34.910 --> 00:49:40.860 align:middle line:90%


00:49:40.860 --> 00:49:41.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:41.740 --> 00:49:43.850 align:middle line:90%
So that didn't work very well.

00:49:43.850 --> 00:49:48.820 align:middle line:90%


00:49:48.820 --> 00:49:51.740 align:middle line:90%
What to do about it.

00:49:51.740 --> 00:49:56.410 align:middle line:84%
There is a theorem that if
A times A times A is small,

00:49:56.410 --> 00:49:59.450 align:middle line:84%
then A times A times
A times A is small.

00:49:59.450 --> 00:50:00.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:50:00.350 --> 00:50:01.850 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: This is
the counterexample

00:50:01.850 --> 00:50:07.250 align:middle line:84%
that you have an
example in SL2 Fp?

00:50:07.250 --> 00:50:09.050 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, it does.

00:50:09.050 --> 00:50:13.690 align:middle line:84%
So H could be any subgroup,
say a Borel subgroup,

00:50:13.690 --> 00:50:15.410 align:middle line:90%
and G is not in there.

00:50:15.410 --> 00:50:17.850 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, this will happen.

00:50:17.850 --> 00:50:19.630 align:middle line:90%
So this could happen in SL2 Fp.

00:50:19.630 --> 00:50:27.158 align:middle line:90%


00:50:27.158 --> 00:50:29.130 align:middle line:84%
So here's a theorem
that if you assume

00:50:29.130 --> 00:50:32.370 align:middle line:84%
that a product of three
copies of A is small,

00:50:32.370 --> 00:50:37.010 align:middle line:84%
then the product of four
copies of A is also small.

00:50:37.010 --> 00:50:39.330 align:middle line:84%
But that theorem is not
immediately useful to us

00:50:39.330 --> 00:50:42.260 align:middle line:84%
because we don't have any input
that a product of three things

00:50:42.260 --> 00:50:42.760 align:middle line:90%
is small.

00:50:42.760 --> 00:50:47.050 align:middle line:90%


00:50:47.050 --> 00:50:49.210 align:middle line:90%
There's another fix to this--

00:50:49.210 --> 00:50:51.370 align:middle line:84%
let's just suppose
think about this example

00:50:51.370 --> 00:50:52.850 align:middle line:90%
and how we might fix it.

00:50:52.850 --> 00:50:56.910 align:middle line:90%


00:50:56.910 --> 00:51:01.350 align:middle line:84%
So this example has a lot
of algebraic structure.

00:51:01.350 --> 00:51:03.550 align:middle line:84%
This is the algebraically
structured part,

00:51:03.550 --> 00:51:05.830 align:middle line:90%
and this is garbage.

00:51:05.830 --> 00:51:11.550 align:middle line:84%
And it would be
helpful to separate A

00:51:11.550 --> 00:51:15.390 align:middle line:84%
into the structured
part and the garbage.

00:51:15.390 --> 00:51:19.150 align:middle line:90%
So how might we do that?

00:51:19.150 --> 00:51:21.050 align:middle line:90%
So let's look at--

00:51:21.050 --> 00:51:24.350 align:middle line:90%


00:51:24.350 --> 00:51:26.480 align:middle line:84%
so this is the continuing
in the example.

00:51:26.480 --> 00:51:31.430 align:middle line:90%


00:51:31.430 --> 00:51:36.470 align:middle line:90%
Let's look at A times A inverse.

00:51:36.470 --> 00:51:39.270 align:middle line:84%
You could do a times-- anyway,
it works a little bit better

00:51:39.270 --> 00:51:40.990 align:middle line:90%
for A times A inverse.

00:51:40.990 --> 00:51:43.110 align:middle line:90%
So what do we have?

00:51:43.110 --> 00:51:49.930 align:middle line:84%
We have H times
H. Actually, yeah,

00:51:49.930 --> 00:51:52.520 align:middle line:84%
so we will eventually
look at A times A inverse,

00:51:52.520 --> 00:51:58.100 align:middle line:84%
but let's think about how
we might separate this.

00:51:58.100 --> 00:52:03.260 align:middle line:84%
So this set has
different pieces.

00:52:03.260 --> 00:52:07.580 align:middle line:84%
And if we want to separate
the algebraic part

00:52:07.580 --> 00:52:11.178 align:middle line:90%
from the garbage--

00:52:11.178 --> 00:52:13.220 align:middle line:84%
so we'd like to find this
part and distinguish it

00:52:13.220 --> 00:52:14.740 align:middle line:90%
from that part.

00:52:14.740 --> 00:52:16.380 align:middle line:84%
How are they different
from each other?

00:52:16.380 --> 00:52:19.900 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's think about
how many representations

00:52:19.900 --> 00:52:23.260 align:middle line:84%
there are for each product
in this product set.

00:52:23.260 --> 00:52:27.620 align:middle line:84%
Any product in here has
many, many representations,

00:52:27.620 --> 00:52:32.740 align:middle line:84%
and the products here have
only one representation.

00:52:32.740 --> 00:52:36.900 align:middle line:84%
So this guy here is the
set of popular products.

00:52:36.900 --> 00:52:39.700 align:middle line:84%
And actually, once
we identified it,

00:52:39.700 --> 00:52:43.840 align:middle line:84%
the popular product set
then is an actual subgroup.

00:52:43.840 --> 00:52:47.460 align:middle line:84%
It has a lot of
algebraic structure.

00:52:47.460 --> 00:52:51.390 align:middle line:84%
Now let that motivate the
following proposition,

00:52:51.390 --> 00:52:53.930 align:middle line:90%
which is an analog of p.

00:52:53.930 --> 00:53:02.730 align:middle line:84%
So it says if A times A inverse
is less than or equal to KA--

00:53:02.730 --> 00:53:04.890 align:middle line:84%
so A inverse, that means
take each element of

00:53:04.890 --> 00:53:05.920 align:middle line:90%
and take its inverse.

00:53:05.920 --> 00:53:10.590 align:middle line:90%


00:53:10.590 --> 00:53:18.650 align:middle line:84%
And then if Q is the set of
popular quotients, so it's

00:53:18.650 --> 00:53:26.170 align:middle line:84%
the set of g so that r A A
inverse of g is bigger than K

00:53:26.170 --> 00:53:36.230 align:middle line:84%
to the something A. Then you can
raise Q to any power you like.

00:53:36.230 --> 00:53:38.260 align:middle line:90%
Q, let's say, we do it L times.

00:53:38.260 --> 00:53:52.800 align:middle line:90%


00:53:52.800 --> 00:53:55.320 align:middle line:84%
Q has a lot of
algebraic structure,

