01:01:14.580 --> 01:01:19.240 align:middle line:90%


01:01:19.240 --> 01:01:22.100 align:middle line:84%
So this finishes the
discussion of theorem 1.

01:01:22.100 --> 01:01:25.200 align:middle line:84%
There's a pretty
detailed proof sketch.

01:01:25.200 --> 01:01:30.200 align:middle line:84%
And it is a somewhat
different setup that shows

01:01:30.200 --> 01:01:33.260 align:middle line:84%
the significance of the idea
of Balog-Szemerédi-Gowers

01:01:33.260 --> 01:01:35.570 align:middle line:84%
and Plünnecke-Ruzsa in
these combinatorial methods.

01:01:35.570 --> 01:01:44.430 align:middle line:90%


01:01:44.430 --> 01:01:48.430 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now in the 15
minutes that's left,

01:01:48.430 --> 01:01:51.270 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to try to say a little
bit about the proof of theorem

01:01:51.270 --> 01:01:52.350 align:middle line:90%
2.

01:01:52.350 --> 01:01:57.230 align:middle line:84%
The proof of theorem
2, it also connects

01:01:57.230 --> 01:02:01.190 align:middle line:84%
with themes of the
class, and especially

01:02:01.190 --> 01:02:03.950 align:middle line:84%
with how some estimates
are different in the case

01:02:03.950 --> 01:02:07.020 align:middle line:84%
of a prime field or the
case of a non-prime field.

01:02:07.020 --> 01:02:41.970 align:middle line:90%


01:02:41.970 --> 01:02:44.070 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:44.070 --> 01:02:47.550 align:middle line:84%
So let's have some let's
do discussion of theorem 2.

01:02:47.550 --> 01:02:53.250 align:middle line:90%


01:02:53.250 --> 01:02:56.670 align:middle line:84%
All right, I'd like to put us
in the following framework.

01:02:56.670 --> 01:03:00.170 align:middle line:84%
We're going to look
at SL2 of k, bar

01:03:00.170 --> 01:03:03.650 align:middle line:84%
where k bar is an
algebraically closed field.

01:03:03.650 --> 01:03:08.010 align:middle line:84%
You could imagine it's the
algebraic closure of Fp.

01:03:08.010 --> 01:03:10.330 align:middle line:84%
All right, and
we're going to look

01:03:10.330 --> 01:03:15.870 align:middle line:90%
at subgroups of SL2 of k bar.

01:03:15.870 --> 01:03:19.930 align:middle line:90%


01:03:19.930 --> 01:03:24.450 align:middle line:90%
Let's remember some easy ones.

01:03:24.450 --> 01:03:28.930 align:middle line:84%
A subgroup like this where A
and A inverse are in this field.

01:03:28.930 --> 01:03:33.250 align:middle line:90%
We have the Borel subgroup.

01:03:33.250 --> 01:03:37.000 align:middle line:90%
So that's A A inverse t.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:39.730 align:middle line:84%
And we have the
unitary subgroup.

01:03:39.730 --> 01:03:47.320 align:middle line:90%


01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:49.720 align:middle line:90%
So those are some subgroups.

01:03:49.720 --> 01:03:52.140 align:middle line:90%
We can take conjugates of them.

01:03:52.140 --> 01:03:53.780 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me
come back to that.

01:03:53.780 --> 01:03:56.100 align:middle line:84%
So then we could do
two general things.

01:03:56.100 --> 01:03:57.386 align:middle line:90%
We can look at subfields.

01:03:57.386 --> 01:04:00.520 align:middle line:90%


01:04:00.520 --> 01:04:06.160 align:middle line:84%
So I can take SL2 k,
where k contained in k bar

01:04:06.160 --> 01:04:08.720 align:middle line:90%
is a subfield.

01:04:08.720 --> 01:04:12.320 align:middle line:84%
Or you could take this
any of with a subfield.

01:04:12.320 --> 01:04:13.520 align:middle line:90%
Those are subgroups.

01:04:13.520 --> 01:04:16.280 align:middle line:90%
And you could take conjugates.

01:04:16.280 --> 01:04:21.180 align:middle line:84%
So conjugate any subgroup
you get, another subgroup.

01:04:21.180 --> 01:04:23.040 align:middle line:84%
So that is a bunch
of subgroups that we

01:04:23.040 --> 01:04:24.960 align:middle line:84%
can identify without
too much trouble that

01:04:24.960 --> 01:04:26.820 align:middle line:90%
sit inside of SL2 of k bar.

01:04:26.820 --> 01:04:29.640 align:middle line:90%


01:04:29.640 --> 01:04:33.810 align:middle line:84%
There is a theorem that says
that this is not exactly,

01:04:33.810 --> 01:04:37.220 align:middle line:84%
but reasonably close
to the fullest.

01:04:37.220 --> 01:04:44.630 align:middle line:90%


01:04:44.630 --> 01:04:49.230 align:middle line:84%
Dickson in 1901 gave
a full classification

01:04:49.230 --> 01:04:52.910 align:middle line:90%
of these subgroups.

01:04:52.910 --> 01:04:54.090 align:middle line:90%
It's a little bit messy.

01:04:54.090 --> 01:04:57.010 align:middle line:84%
It includes a variety of finite
subgroups in certain cases

01:04:57.010 --> 01:04:59.270 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

01:04:59.270 --> 01:05:06.230 align:middle line:84%
His theorem implies that
if H is an actual subgroup,

01:05:06.230 --> 01:05:19.190 align:middle line:84%
then either H is contained in
a conjugate of SL2 k, where

01:05:19.190 --> 01:05:41.073 align:middle line:84%
k is a subfield, or most of H is
contained in a conjugate of L.

01:05:41.073 --> 01:05:42.740 align:middle line:84%
If we know from the
beginning that we're

01:05:42.740 --> 01:05:46.800 align:middle line:84%
talking about a subgroup of SL2
of Fp, a proper subgroup of SL2,

01:05:46.800 --> 01:05:48.760 align:middle line:84%
Fp, it eliminates
the first case.

01:05:48.760 --> 01:05:52.100 align:middle line:84%
So we must be in
the second case.

01:05:52.100 --> 01:05:52.720 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:05:52.720 --> 01:05:56.140 align:middle line:90%


01:05:56.140 --> 01:05:58.620 align:middle line:90%
But Dickson's methods are--

01:05:58.620 --> 01:06:00.880 align:middle line:84%
some of them, at least,
are not very robust

01:06:00.880 --> 01:06:03.020 align:middle line:84%
if you replace the
hypothesis of being

01:06:03.020 --> 01:06:06.700 align:middle line:84%
an actual subgroup by something
like H times H times H times H

01:06:06.700 --> 01:06:09.620 align:middle line:90%
times H is pretty small.

01:06:09.620 --> 01:06:11.820 align:middle line:84%
So here's a common
example of a technique

01:06:11.820 --> 01:06:14.020 align:middle line:84%
that we use to
classify subgroups

01:06:14.020 --> 01:06:16.260 align:middle line:84%
that does not do very
well if we replace it

01:06:16.260 --> 01:06:18.020 align:middle line:90%
by approximate subgroups.

01:06:18.020 --> 01:06:21.780 align:middle line:84%
Example is there's the
order of the subgroup

01:06:21.780 --> 01:06:24.220 align:middle line:90%
divides the order of the group.

01:06:24.220 --> 01:06:27.100 align:middle line:90%
That's really useful in 18.701.

01:06:27.100 --> 01:06:29.420 align:middle line:84%
You want to classify the
subgroups of subgroup

01:06:29.420 --> 01:06:31.410 align:middle line:90%
with eight elements.

01:06:31.410 --> 01:06:34.370 align:middle line:84%
But something like
that is not going

01:06:34.370 --> 01:06:39.330 align:middle line:84%
to survive an approximate
subgroup in any useful way.

01:06:39.330 --> 01:06:41.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:41.010 --> 01:06:43.850 align:middle line:84%
So the proof of
theorem 2 is based

01:06:43.850 --> 01:06:49.670 align:middle line:84%
on a rather different strategy
for this classification.

01:06:49.670 --> 01:06:51.350 align:middle line:90%
That's due to Larsen and Pink.

01:06:51.350 --> 01:06:54.730 align:middle line:90%


01:06:54.730 --> 01:07:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So let me say part A, which is
the Larsen and Pink strategy.

01:07:00.680 --> 01:07:05.130 align:middle line:90%


01:07:05.130 --> 01:07:06.650 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:07:06.650 --> 01:07:14.410 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to think about
how a subgroup intersects

01:07:14.410 --> 01:07:17.810 align:middle line:90%
these subgroups.

01:07:17.810 --> 01:07:23.810 align:middle line:84%
So if you take SL2 k and you
intersect it with one of these,

01:07:23.810 --> 01:07:28.170 align:middle line:84%
it will either be empty, or
just be identity or something

01:07:28.170 --> 01:07:32.580 align:middle line:84%
like that, or it will be a
subgroup that's like T0 of k.

01:07:32.580 --> 01:07:35.720 align:middle line:90%


01:07:35.720 --> 01:07:46.480 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to study H
intersected with T of k bar,

01:07:46.480 --> 01:07:54.120 align:middle line:84%
H intersected with B of k bar,
H intersected with U of k bar.

01:07:54.120 --> 01:07:56.920 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see the
following behavior.

01:07:56.920 --> 01:08:04.280 align:middle line:84%
The H intersected with T of
k bar is roughly H to the 1/3

01:08:04.280 --> 01:08:05.940 align:middle line:90%
or big O of 1.

01:08:05.940 --> 01:08:14.480 align:middle line:90%


01:08:14.480 --> 01:08:17.880 align:middle line:84%
So if I take SL2 Fp and
I intersect it with this,

01:08:17.880 --> 01:08:19.740 align:middle line:90%
I'll get T0 of Fp.

01:08:19.740 --> 01:08:22.120 align:middle line:84%
It'll be about p of those,
which is about the cube

01:08:22.120 --> 01:08:25.000 align:middle line:90%
root of the size of SL2 Fp.

01:08:25.000 --> 01:08:28.620 align:middle line:84%
If I take some crazy torus
in the algebraic closure

01:08:28.620 --> 01:08:32.380 align:middle line:84%
that may not intersect
except at the identity.

01:08:32.380 --> 01:08:36.060 align:middle line:84%
So these are the two
things that could happen.

01:08:36.060 --> 01:08:37.720 align:middle line:90%
And then similarly with these.

01:08:37.720 --> 01:08:56.640 align:middle line:90%


01:08:56.640 --> 01:08:59.939 align:middle line:84%
So they first proved that if
you take an arbitrary group

01:08:59.939 --> 01:09:02.060 align:middle line:84%
and you consider
how it intersects

01:09:02.060 --> 01:09:05.300 align:middle line:84%
these kind of fundamental
algebraic subgroups,

01:09:05.300 --> 01:09:10.779 align:middle line:84%
then it behaves a lot like
it were SL2 of a subfield.

01:09:10.779 --> 01:09:13.460 align:middle line:84%
And then building
from this, they

01:09:13.460 --> 01:09:15.859 align:middle line:84%
were able to see that
actually, it would

01:09:15.859 --> 01:09:19.020 align:middle line:90%
have to be SL2 of a subfield.

01:09:19.020 --> 01:09:21.520 align:middle line:84%
So that's their approach to
the rough classification.

01:09:21.520 --> 01:09:24.180 align:middle line:90%


01:09:24.180 --> 01:09:29.147 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so this was a cool
paper in pure group.

01:09:29.147 --> 01:09:31.189 align:middle line:84%
They weren't interested
in approximate subgroups.

01:09:31.189 --> 01:09:33.970 align:middle line:84%
They were interested in
pure group theory problem,

01:09:33.970 --> 01:09:37.463 align:middle line:84%
classifying subgroups
of SLD of k,

01:09:37.463 --> 01:09:40.879 align:middle line:84%
or other like groups
over finite fields.

01:09:40.879 --> 01:09:43.450 align:middle line:90%


01:09:43.450 --> 01:09:45.370 align:middle line:84%
The complete classification
is clearly hard

01:09:45.370 --> 01:09:48.930 align:middle line:84%
because any finite group embeds
in a permutation group which

01:09:48.930 --> 01:09:51.649 align:middle line:90%
embeds an SLD of Fp.

01:09:51.649 --> 01:09:56.250 align:middle line:84%
So all finite groups occur
as subgroups of SLD of Fp

01:09:56.250 --> 01:09:59.290 align:middle line:90%
for some D and some p.

01:09:59.290 --> 01:10:01.970 align:middle line:84%
And so it's not really
plausible to give

01:10:01.970 --> 01:10:04.240 align:middle line:84%
a complete classification,
or anyway, it

01:10:04.240 --> 01:10:06.490 align:middle line:84%
would be at least as hard
as classifying finite groups

01:10:06.490 --> 01:10:08.490 align:middle line:84%
to give a complete
classification,

01:10:08.490 --> 01:10:10.850 align:middle line:84%
but they were able
to classify, I

01:10:10.850 --> 01:10:14.290 align:middle line:84%
think it's subgroups
of SLD of Fp, which

01:10:14.290 --> 01:10:17.250 align:middle line:84%
have at least some size,
like p to the epsilon

01:10:17.250 --> 01:10:20.130 align:middle line:84%
or epsilon times D or something
like this, the ones that

01:10:20.130 --> 01:10:21.170 align:middle line:90%
are decently large.

01:10:21.170 --> 01:10:23.930 align:middle line:90%


01:10:23.930 --> 01:10:25.780 align:middle line:90%
That Was in around 2000.

01:10:25.780 --> 01:10:28.000 align:middle line:90%
So this really is a hard thing.

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:32.000 align:middle line:84%
But it also turns out that
their method interacts

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:35.200 align:middle line:84%
well with just assuming that
H times H times H times H

01:10:35.200 --> 01:10:37.080 align:middle line:90%
is small.

01:10:37.080 --> 01:10:42.000 align:middle line:84%
So here, this whole
argument works

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:51.509 align:middle line:84%
if we just assume that H times
H times H times H times H

01:10:51.509 --> 01:10:55.840 align:middle line:90%
is equal to H. OK.

01:10:55.840 --> 01:10:57.720 align:middle line:84%
I may or may not
have two minutes

01:10:57.720 --> 01:11:00.840 align:middle line:84%
to try to describe what they
did, how this part works.

01:11:00.840 --> 01:11:03.380 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Significance
of the algebraic closure.

01:11:03.380 --> 01:11:08.640 align:middle line:84%
If we only care about
subgroups of SL2 Fp,

01:11:08.640 --> 01:11:12.053 align:middle line:84%
what information are you
gaining from intersecting with--

01:11:12.053 --> 01:11:13.720 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah,
so the question is,

01:11:13.720 --> 01:11:16.000 align:middle line:84%
Why bring into play
the algebraic closure?

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:18.628 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Also, what is the
algebraic closure of Fp?

01:11:18.628 --> 01:11:20.920 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: And what is
the algebraic closure of Fp?

01:11:20.920 --> 01:11:21.420 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:11:21.420 --> 01:11:34.250 align:middle line:90%


01:11:34.250 --> 01:11:38.270 align:middle line:84%
You do need this for the
following reason that

01:11:38.270 --> 01:11:41.990 align:middle line:84%
should be familiar to
us even as analysts.

01:11:41.990 --> 01:11:46.110 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you have
a matrix in SL2 r,

01:11:46.110 --> 01:11:48.370 align:middle line:84%
and you would like
to diagonalize it.

01:11:48.370 --> 01:11:50.670 align:middle line:84%
You'd like to look at its
eigenvalues, or whatever.

01:11:50.670 --> 01:11:57.510 align:middle line:84%
Well, you can't necessarily
do that in SL2 r,

01:11:57.510 --> 01:11:59.770 align:middle line:84%
because the eigenvalues
could be complex.

01:11:59.770 --> 01:12:03.070 align:middle line:84%
So in order to diagonalize it,
you might want to move to SL2 c.

01:12:03.070 --> 01:12:05.310 align:middle line:84%
And diagonalizing
matrices is useful

01:12:05.310 --> 01:12:10.510 align:middle line:84%
because you can
classify matrices

01:12:10.510 --> 01:12:12.130 align:middle line:90%
by their Jordan canonical form.

01:12:12.130 --> 01:12:14.990 align:middle line:84%
And this is a convenient
way to organize things.

01:12:14.990 --> 01:12:17.270 align:middle line:84%
That's the same thing
that's going on here.

01:12:17.270 --> 01:12:19.670 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The intersections
look the same, though.

01:12:19.670 --> 01:12:23.540 align:middle line:84%
The intersection of if H is
just a subgroup of SL2 of k,

01:12:23.540 --> 01:12:25.740 align:middle line:84%
then the intersection
with T k bar

01:12:25.740 --> 01:12:27.660 align:middle line:84%
is the same as the
intersection of T k.

01:12:27.660 --> 01:12:29.160 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah,
that's correct.

01:12:29.160 --> 01:12:30.080 align:middle line:90%
That's correct.

01:12:30.080 --> 01:12:36.140 align:middle line:84%
But OK, so the
comment was that if--

01:12:36.140 --> 01:12:43.140 align:middle line:84%
so what did this--
so if H is in SL2 k,

01:12:43.140 --> 01:12:47.900 align:middle line:84%
then H intersected
with T0 of k bar

01:12:47.900 --> 01:12:53.720 align:middle line:84%
is the same thing as H
intersected with T0 of k.

01:12:53.720 --> 01:12:54.220 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:12:54.220 --> 01:12:54.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:54.720 --> 01:12:56.180 align:middle line:84%
I think the problem
with is that I

01:12:56.180 --> 01:12:58.220 align:middle line:84%
forgot to say something about
what's written on the board

01:12:58.220 --> 01:12:58.820 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:12:58.820 --> 01:13:02.460 align:middle line:90%
This T is not T0.

01:13:02.460 --> 01:13:04.840 align:middle line:84%
The conjugates are
really important.

01:13:04.840 --> 01:13:12.420 align:middle line:84%
So T of k bar is a
conjugate of T0 of k bar.

01:13:12.420 --> 01:13:13.220 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:13:13.220 --> 01:13:16.940 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Are the elements
that are being diagonalized

01:13:16.940 --> 01:13:20.980 align:middle line:84%
just elements of SL2 or
bigger linear operators

01:13:20.980 --> 01:13:23.850 align:middle line:90%
responding to SL2?

01:13:23.850 --> 01:13:28.610 align:middle line:84%
I think if it's just SL2, you
only need a degree-2 extension.

01:13:28.610 --> 01:13:29.730 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:13:29.730 --> 01:13:31.210 align:middle line:84%
So the comment is
that if we just

01:13:31.210 --> 01:13:34.370 align:middle line:84%
want to diagonalize
matrices in SL2 Fp,

01:13:34.370 --> 01:13:38.570 align:middle line:84%
we probably only need a degree-2
extension of Fp, which we might

01:13:38.570 --> 01:13:40.370 align:middle line:90%
feel more comfortable with.

01:13:40.370 --> 01:13:41.630 align:middle line:90%
I think that's probably right.

01:13:41.630 --> 01:13:44.088 align:middle line:84%
I think we could probably work
with the degree-2 extension.

01:13:44.088 --> 01:13:46.910 align:middle line:90%


01:13:46.910 --> 01:13:47.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:47.410 --> 01:14:17.290 align:middle line:90%


01:14:17.290 --> 01:14:18.410 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:14:18.410 --> 01:14:29.770 align:middle line:84%
So the output of the Larsen-Pink
argument is after conjugating.

01:14:29.770 --> 01:14:32.910 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so first of
all, we can arrange

01:14:32.910 --> 01:14:39.650 align:middle line:84%
that our H intersected with
some unitary guy, is pretty big.

01:14:39.650 --> 01:14:43.630 align:middle line:90%


01:14:43.630 --> 01:14:49.070 align:middle line:84%
After conjugating, we can
arrange that this is U0 of k.

01:14:49.070 --> 01:15:00.590 align:middle line:84%
So H contains some guys like
this, where T is in some subset

01:15:00.590 --> 01:15:03.450 align:middle line:84%
that I'll call E.
And E is pretty big.

01:15:03.450 --> 01:15:12.150 align:middle line:90%


01:15:12.150 --> 01:15:15.230 align:middle line:84%
Moreover, this part
should not expand

01:15:15.230 --> 01:15:18.780 align:middle line:90%
too much when we take products.

01:15:18.780 --> 01:15:25.720 align:middle line:84%
So here, let's call this
thing a unitary piece of H.

01:15:25.720 --> 01:15:29.552 align:middle line:84%
UH times UH, also, this
isn't completely obvious,

01:15:29.552 --> 01:15:31.260 align:middle line:84%
but it's not that
difficult. It shouldn't

01:15:31.260 --> 01:15:33.340 align:middle line:90%
be that much bigger than.

01:15:33.340 --> 01:15:37.100 align:middle line:84%
And that tells us that E
plus E shouldn't be that much

01:15:37.100 --> 01:15:45.820 align:middle line:84%
bigger than E.
Also, we should have

01:15:45.820 --> 01:15:53.200 align:middle line:84%
this U is in some B, and
H intersect B of k bar.

01:15:53.200 --> 01:15:56.300 align:middle line:90%


01:15:56.300 --> 01:15:59.360 align:middle line:84%
So we've already
conjugated so that U is U0.

01:15:59.360 --> 01:16:01.580 align:middle line:90%
So this is going to be B0.

01:16:01.580 --> 01:16:04.830 align:middle line:84%
And this should be
around H to the 2/3.

01:16:04.830 --> 01:16:11.020 align:middle line:90%


01:16:11.020 --> 01:16:16.220 align:middle line:84%
Inside of there, we'll have a T.
And H intersect that should be

01:16:16.220 --> 01:16:19.250 align:middle line:90%
like H to the 1/3.

01:16:19.250 --> 01:16:22.850 align:middle line:90%
So H intersect T0 k bar.

01:16:22.850 --> 01:16:25.000 align:middle line:84%
That's going to be some
guys that look like this.

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:27.850 align:middle line:90%


01:16:27.850 --> 01:16:30.570 align:middle line:84%
And these A's live
in some set that I'll

01:16:30.570 --> 01:16:37.090 align:middle line:84%
call F. So then if you think
about how these matrices act

01:16:37.090 --> 01:16:41.890 align:middle line:84%
on these matrices,
we should get--

01:16:41.890 --> 01:16:51.890 align:middle line:84%
so T0-- so let's called this
guy the T part of H. And U,

01:16:51.890 --> 01:16:52.510 align:middle line:90%
say, here.

01:16:52.510 --> 01:16:55.850 align:middle line:90%


01:16:55.850 --> 01:16:58.330 align:middle line:90%
Well, OK.

01:16:58.330 --> 01:17:02.850 align:middle line:84%
This thing here is
the B part of H.

01:17:02.850 --> 01:17:05.970 align:middle line:84%
So the B part of H
times the B part of H

01:17:05.970 --> 01:17:11.490 align:middle line:84%
should be not that much
bigger than the B part of H.

01:17:11.490 --> 01:17:16.800 align:middle line:84%
And if you unwind what that
means, you multiply these,

01:17:16.800 --> 01:17:23.720 align:middle line:84%
you'll have things like a a
inverse at, where a is an F,

01:17:23.720 --> 01:17:30.200 align:middle line:84%
t is an E. So the conclusion
is that E times F is also not

01:17:30.200 --> 01:17:46.200 align:middle line:90%
that much bigger than E or F.

01:17:46.200 --> 01:17:50.280 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, once you
have a unipotent piece where

01:17:50.280 --> 01:17:54.080 align:middle line:84%
you have these guys, then
this multiplication operation

01:17:54.080 --> 01:17:56.760 align:middle line:84%
just gives you addition
of the numbers in here.

01:17:56.760 --> 01:17:59.240 align:middle line:90%
So you have a simpler thing.

01:17:59.240 --> 01:18:04.200 align:middle line:84%
And then once you have a bunch
of upper triangular guys,

01:18:04.200 --> 01:18:16.150 align:middle line:84%
then this matrix
multiplication induces

01:18:16.150 --> 01:18:18.920 align:middle line:84%
this regular multiplication,
and we have small products.

01:18:18.920 --> 01:18:22.950 align:middle line:90%


01:18:22.950 --> 01:18:25.030 align:middle line:84%
This is consistent
with the possibility

01:18:25.030 --> 01:18:28.630 align:middle line:84%
that E and F could both
be just some subfield k

01:18:28.630 --> 01:18:31.310 align:middle line:90%
or some approximate subfield.

01:18:31.310 --> 01:18:33.270 align:middle line:84%
But the sum product
theorem says that Fp

01:18:33.270 --> 01:18:35.530 align:middle line:90%
has no approximate subfields.

01:18:35.530 --> 01:18:37.942 align:middle line:84%
And so the subproduct theorem
rules out the possibility

01:18:37.942 --> 01:18:38.900 align:middle line:90%
that this could happen.

01:18:38.900 --> 01:18:41.550 align:middle line:90%


01:18:41.550 --> 01:18:47.670 align:middle line:84%
So the conclusion is
the sum product theorem

01:18:47.670 --> 01:18:49.760 align:middle line:90%
applies that this can't happen.

01:18:49.760 --> 01:19:07.750 align:middle line:90%


01:19:07.750 --> 01:19:08.770 align:middle line:90%
What's on the board?

01:19:08.770 --> 01:19:10.530 align:middle line:90%
Let me I should add one thing.

01:19:10.530 --> 01:19:16.530 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to assume that H
is not contained in a Borel guy.

01:19:16.530 --> 01:19:23.620 align:middle line:90%


01:19:23.620 --> 01:19:26.180 align:middle line:84%
So this whole
thing that wouldn't

01:19:26.180 --> 01:19:28.340 align:middle line:90%
be true for the Borel subgroup.

01:19:28.340 --> 01:19:29.400 align:middle line:90%
It's only true.

01:19:29.400 --> 01:19:33.000 align:middle line:84%
Once we assume that our subgroup
is not contained in Borel,

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:34.300 align:middle line:90%
and then we get this.

01:19:34.300 --> 01:19:40.700 align:middle line:84%
And that tells us that the
intersection sizes have

01:19:40.700 --> 01:19:43.580 align:middle line:90%
to match SL2 of a subfield.

01:19:43.580 --> 01:19:45.820 align:middle line:84%
And then if you
look more carefully

01:19:45.820 --> 01:19:49.120 align:middle line:84%
at the matrices that appear
in the intersections,

01:19:49.120 --> 01:19:51.180 align:middle line:84%
you see that the
entries there have

01:19:51.180 --> 01:19:53.302 align:middle line:90%
to be kind of like a subfield.

01:19:53.302 --> 01:19:55.260 align:middle line:84%
And then it becomes a
question of whether there

01:19:55.260 --> 01:19:56.760 align:middle line:90%
are approximate subfields.

01:19:56.760 --> 01:20:01.960 align:middle line:90%


01:20:01.960 --> 01:20:02.460 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:20:02.460 --> 01:20:06.300 align:middle line:84%
Let me say it one more time, and
then we will break for the week.

01:20:06.300 --> 01:20:10.580 align:middle line:84%
So the theorem says that if you
have a subgroup, which is not

01:20:10.580 --> 01:20:13.120 align:middle line:84%
pretty much contained in
a Borel subgroup, then

01:20:13.120 --> 01:20:15.970 align:middle line:90%
it must be SL2 of a subfield.

01:20:15.970 --> 01:20:21.000 align:middle line:90%


01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:23.100 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be
true for subgroups,

01:20:23.100 --> 01:20:25.360 align:middle line:84%
but it's also true for
approximate subgroups.

01:20:25.360 --> 01:20:27.340 align:middle line:84%
So imagine we have an
approximate subgroup,

01:20:27.340 --> 01:20:29.040 align:middle line:84%
we're going to
gradually prove that it

01:20:29.040 --> 01:20:33.160 align:middle line:84%
has more and more properties
of SL2 over a finite field.

01:20:33.160 --> 01:20:35.360 align:middle line:84%
So the first property
we will consider

01:20:35.360 --> 01:20:39.880 align:middle line:84%
is how it intersects
various algebraic subgroups

01:20:39.880 --> 01:20:42.440 align:middle line:90%
of SL2 of k bar.

01:20:42.440 --> 01:20:44.440 align:middle line:84%
The sizes of those
intersections behave

01:20:44.440 --> 01:20:46.240 align:middle line:84%
in a way that matches
what you would

01:20:46.240 --> 01:20:49.840 align:middle line:90%
expect from SL2 of a subfield.

01:20:49.840 --> 01:20:53.160 align:middle line:84%
There's a substantial thing
to say about this proof

01:20:53.160 --> 01:20:56.880 align:middle line:84%
that we won't have time
to do in this class.

01:20:56.880 --> 01:21:00.360 align:middle line:84%
But once you know
that, these subgroups

01:21:00.360 --> 01:21:02.720 align:middle line:84%
are useful because
the matrices in here

01:21:02.720 --> 01:21:05.600 align:middle line:84%
are simpler than
general 2 by 2 matrices.

01:21:05.600 --> 01:21:09.290 align:middle line:84%
So the unitary subgroup has
matrices that look like this.

01:21:09.290 --> 01:21:10.790 align:middle line:84%
And when you multiply
them, you just

01:21:10.790 --> 01:21:12.510 align:middle line:90%
add the upper right hand corner.

01:21:12.510 --> 01:21:15.330 align:middle line:84%
And so now if you just look at
these upper right-hand corners,

01:21:15.330 --> 01:21:17.190 align:middle line:84%
you see that adding
those numbers

01:21:17.190 --> 01:21:18.450 align:middle line:90%
doesn't change very much.

01:21:18.450 --> 01:21:20.470 align:middle line:90%
That's a property of a subfield.

01:21:20.470 --> 01:21:22.230 align:middle line:84%
So it's behaving
like a subfield.

01:21:22.230 --> 01:21:28.630 align:middle line:84%
And the upper diagonal matrices,
the multiplication rule

01:21:28.630 --> 01:21:30.370 align:middle line:84%
is only a little bit
more complicated.

01:21:30.370 --> 01:21:33.510 align:middle line:84%
It's a pretty simple mix of
multiplication and addition.

01:21:33.510 --> 01:21:36.610 align:middle line:84%
So you could see that
these diagonal entries,

01:21:36.610 --> 01:21:39.630 align:middle line:84%
they should be almost
closed under multiplication.

01:21:39.630 --> 01:21:41.210 align:middle line:84%
And they interact
with each other.

01:21:41.210 --> 01:21:43.242 align:middle line:84%
And so you would get
something like this.

01:21:43.242 --> 01:21:44.950 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, all those
things being consistent

01:21:44.950 --> 01:21:48.510 align:middle line:84%
algebraically with
being a subfield.

01:21:48.510 --> 01:21:49.450 align:middle line:90%
OK, yeah.

01:21:49.450 --> 01:21:50.615 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Could we use 2.5?

01:21:50.615 --> 01:21:53.776 align:middle line:90%


01:21:53.776 --> 01:21:55.276 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Where
did we use 2.5?

01:21:55.276 --> 01:22:11.060 align:middle line:90%


01:22:11.060 --> 01:22:13.740 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's a good question.

01:22:13.740 --> 01:22:16.080 align:middle line:84%
Actually, I don't see
where we used that here.

01:22:16.080 --> 01:22:21.100 align:middle line:90%


01:22:21.100 --> 01:22:24.400 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, we used that here.

01:22:24.400 --> 01:22:27.620 align:middle line:84%
So at the end, we have to say
E and F cannot be approximately

01:22:27.620 --> 01:22:29.060 align:middle line:90%
a subfield.

01:22:29.060 --> 01:22:33.860 align:middle line:84%
And that requires that they're
significantly smaller than Fp.

01:22:33.860 --> 01:22:37.040 align:middle line:84%
So if you take Fp and you
remove two or three elements,

01:22:37.040 --> 01:22:39.760 align:middle line:84%
it is almost closed under
addition and multiplication.

01:22:39.760 --> 01:22:42.860 align:middle line:84%
So this could happen
then if you were allowed

01:22:42.860 --> 01:22:46.880 align:middle line:84%
to take a really large subset of
Fp, a really large subset of SL2

01:22:46.880 --> 01:22:47.380 align:middle line:90%
Fp.

01:22:47.380 --> 01:22:54.020 align:middle line:90%


01:22:54.020 --> 01:22:54.920 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

01:22:54.920 --> 01:22:56.200 align:middle line:90%
I apologize for going over.

01:22:56.200 --> 01:22:57.820 align:middle line:90%
Thanks for your patience.

01:22:57.820 --> 01:22:59.080 align:middle line:90%
Have a good weekend.

01:22:59.080 --> 01:23:01.370 align:middle line:90%
I will see you next week.

01:23:01.370 --> 01:23:09.000 align:middle line:90%